Question:
Mrs P is at your clinic for a routine check up but mentions she'd been feeling a bit of bloating and discomfort in her "tum" recently, but she reckons it's because it's because she's recently gone vegan and all the greens are "doing a number" on her. You carry out a precautionary ultrasound on the abdomen and stumble across this...

What's your diagnosis?
Explanation:
I'm pretty proud of this question...

 

•Tumours they will always show up as solid grey/white masses, not black masses, black indicates liquid because the sound wave goes straight through it.

 

•Polycystic Ovaries Syndrome ISN'T the same as Ovarian Cysts, Polycystic ovaries are as a result of other follicles maturing along side the dominant follicle and often causes failure for the follicle to ovulate, playing havoc with your hormones and hence has much more severe symptoms. How you could have known this from the ultrasound is that the cysts are all small, similar sizes and usually around the follicular development pathway, like shown below:

•Ovarian Cysts are almost completely benign fluid filled sacks on the ovaries, and hence is the correct answer

•Dermoid Cysts are the very unusual version of the ovarian cysts that contain teeth and hair derived from abnormal growth of the embryonic stem cells, meaning the ultrasound would not be clear black but patchy grey

Question:
You have a patient who is male and 88kg, who you believe has kidney failure, so you carry out a creatinine clearance test. You compare the results to a woman of the same age, who is 60kg. The results are below:

 

Man:          450mmol serum creatinine 

Woman:     140mmol serum creatinine

 

Who has the highest GFR?
Explanation:
The creatinine test is a measure of your Glomerular Filtration Rate (GFR) because the chemical creatinine (waste products of muscles) is almost completely cleared from blood serum to tubular fluid by the kidneys (i.e. none is resorbed), so by measuring serum creatinine and urine creatinine you would hope that these 2 values would be fairly close to indicate your kidneys are functioning well.

 

In this case I've only given the serum concentration to make it a bit trickier, but you should be able to see that because of the significantly raised serum creatine compared to a "norm" value provided by the woman, the man is not clearing his creatinine properly so it's accumulating in his blood. Therefore he has the lower GFR, because it's practically non existent.

 

The final sting in the tail of this question is the fact that creatinine is the waste product of the muscles source of energy creatine phosphate, and because of a male's tendency to have a larger muscle mass (emphasized by his 88kg weight), you would actually expect him to have a higher serum creatinine than the woman, but it's important to appreciate that often mens GFR's increase to compensate for this and usually male and female serum creatinines should be similar.

Question: NSAIDs can cause stomach ulcers by...
OptionA: Reducing prostaglandins(PG-Es) required for vasodilation to thicken the gastric walls and synthesise HCO3-
OptionB: Filling H2 receptor pumps, mimicking the shape of Histamine to activate Gs proteins in the parietal cells resulting in the adenyl cyclase cAMP cascade to activate PKA resulting in stimulation of the H+/K proton pump and overproduction of stomach HCl
OptionC: Reducing prostaglandins which usually activate Gi proteins in the parietal that inhibit the adenyl cyclase/cAMP cascade mentioned above so the proton pump is less regulated and more HCl is produced
OptionD: Prostaglandins usually inhibit the gastrin receptor on the parietal cell that usually would activate the Gq protein in the cell leading to the activation of PIP2, resulting in its separation into DAG which activates PKC on the cell membrane and IP3 which releases intracellular calcium from the ER to further activate PKC which in turn, would have activated the H+/K proton pump resulting in production of stomach acid
Explanation:
A and C is right, it works by 2 mechanisms (if not more)

B is how antacids(H2 agonists) work but instead of filling and activating they competitively inhibit

D is how CCK works

Question: What node is not a superficial lymph node?
Explanation:
The lymph nodes of the head and neck are divided into superficial and deep lymph nodes

 

The superficial lymph nodes are: occipital, mastoid, pre-auricular, parotid, submental, submandibular, facial and superficial cervical

Question: A glucose transporter is said to have a "high Km", what does this mean for the transporter and which transporter is it most likely to be?
Explanation:
Km = Enzyme affinity (e.g. how little substrate there can be around for the transporter to channel it across the membrane)

Km = Substrate concontration at which 1/2 the Vmax is reached

 

The lower the Km value, the less substrate is required, so the better the enzyme is

 

•GLUT2 and GLUT4 are the insulin pathway involved transporters

•GLUT2 is on the insulin monitoring cells in the pancreas and liver (e.g. islet of langerhans), and has a high Km because it only needs to open when theres too much glucose about to signal that insulin needs to be released to counteract it.

•GLUT4 is on the muscle cells and has a low Km because they need glucose all the time so these transporters should remain open at lower concentrations of glucose in the blood.

 

Love Sam

Question: What is associated with the frontal lobe?
Explanation:
The frontal lobe is associated with higher intellect, social conduct, mood, personality and language.

 

Language is associated with the frontal lobe. However, calculation is not. Calculation and language are both associated with the parietal lobe.

 

The temporal lobe is associated with memory and language. It is also responsible for hearing as it contains the primary auditory cortex.

 

The occipital lobe contains the primary visual cortex and is therefore responsible for vision.

Question: What is the sequence of events that leads to an overdose of paracetamol causing hepatocyte damage?
OptionA: Over-saturation of CYP enzymes = Increased use of the UGT pathway = Increased NAPBQI = Depleted glutathione = Innability to conjugate the toxic NAPBQI.
OptionB: Low rate of action for UGT enzymes = Decreased production of NAPBQI = Decreased hepatocyte function due to depleted NAPBQI
OptionC: Defect in the MRP2 transporter = Glutathione-conjugated NAPBQI cannot be passed to the bile canaliculi = Unable to excrete into the gut and therefore NAPBQI cannot be eliminated from the body
OptionD: Over-saturation of UGT enzymes = Increased use of the CYP pathway = Increased NAPBQI = Depleted glutathione = Innability to conjugate the toxic NAPBQI = Innability to excrete NAPBQI
Explanation:
When there is an overdose of paracetamol:-

- UGT enzymes get oversaturated (this is the normal pathway of elimination)

-The excess paracetamol is taken up by the CYP enzyme pathway

-CYP1A2 & CYP2E1 produce phase 1 toxic NAPBQI

-This is conjugated by glutathione in the liver (similar to how glucuronic acid conjugates bilirubin)

-Glutathione reserves are dried up and NAPBQI cannot be conjugated further to form a water-soluable substance

- NAPBQI accumulates in the liver due to it not being able to be excreted

-NAPBQI is toxic to hepatocytes

 

A is incorrect due to the UGT and CYP enzymes being the wrong way around.

B is incorrect as there is a high rate of action for UGT enzymes in paracetamol OD, this increases the amount of NAPBQI and NAPBQI would lead to decreased function of the hepatocytes as opposed to increased function.

C is incorrect as it discusses the MRP2 transporter which is used for excreting bilirubin into the bile canaliculi

Question: What is precursor molecule for synthesis of all steroid hormones?
Explanation: All steroid hormones are synthesised from cholesterol. The first step is always conversion to pregnenolone. Androstenedione is a sex steroid precursor to oestrogens. Long-chain hydrocarbons are fats used for energy. Tyrosine is an amino acid used to make catecholamines and thyroid hormones.

Question: Testosterone is produced by Leidig cells in response to:
Explanation:
Pituitary LH stimulates the Leidig cells to produce androgens, including testosterone. LH increases the activity of an enzyme associated with the conversion of cholesterol to pregnenolone, therefore leading to testosterone synthesis.

Prolactin does actually have a role in this too, as it increases the sensitivity of Leidig cells to LH, therefore increasing testosterone production. But without LH, the Leidig cells would not be stimulated at all.

Question: Which one of these proteins of the coagulation cascade does warfarin NOT inhibit?
Explanation:
This question is aimed to help appreciate the difference between your anti-platelet drugs (Aspirin, GIIb/IIIa inhibitors, Prasugrel) and your antithrombin drugs (Warfarin, Heparin, Xa agonists) which were actually quite badly covered last term. Heres all you need to know:

 

 

It's a great way to help learn your coagulation cascade:

 

•Warfarin, because it's a long term use drug, tends to effect proteins further up the line to other drugs because you don't want to exert an extreme effect if you're taking it for ages. So it tends to inhibit around 1 key protein from each pathway, Extrinsic being VII, Intrinsic being IX and X, and Common being Prothrombin (II). These are actually the key proteins of the coagulation cascade to help you remember it's structure. Proteins like VIII and V actually play a relatively small role by comparison. This second diagram illustrates that point nicely:

•Heparin, basically warfarin's "immediate response" brother, because it's a much more short term resolve drug, it goes straight in for the kill with inhibiting the most important proteins of the cascade Xa, and Thrombin.

 

If you're still finding it hard to visualise the coagulation cascade, I found this video amazing:

Hope this helps,

Love Sam

Question: What type of drugs are Statins?
Explanation:
It may seem this question is pedantic, but we do need to know what class of drug statins are because they're commonly prescribed along side the anticoagulants (Antithrombins/Anti-platelets) for the reason that they focus on a completely different area of the problem, the cholesterol in the LDLs thats the heart of the atherosclerotic plaque. All the chemicals are part of the livers break down of chylomicrons.

 

1) Lipoprotein Lipase: Breaks down the original chylomicron and the resulting VLDLs and IDLs, to release fatty acids from the triglycerides to form adipose tissue

2) Hepatic Lipase: Breaks the IDLs into LDLs to transport the left over cholesterol to the muscles for use as hormones 

3) HMG CoA inhibitor: Was just me being mean

4) HMG CoA reductase inhibitor: Converts the Acetyl CoA from the broken down chylomicrons, VLDL and IDL into Mevalonate which then becomes cholesterol

5) ABCA1 Agonist: Receptors that activate on the muscle tissue when there's an excess of LDL in the system to tell HDL to collect some of the LDL and return it to the liver for breakdown.

 

I find that it's just worth rope learning the name, but we're also assessed on our knowledge of Chylomicron metabolism by the liver which I feel I've explained badly here but the geeky medics page on it is incredible and doesn't take long to get your head around. I'll put the link below:

http://geekymedics.com/cholesterol-metabolism/

 

Love Sam

Question: What two cranial nerves do not join the brainstem?

Question: What part of the brain produces Cerebrospinal Fluid (CSF)?
Explanation:
CSF is produced by the Choroid Plexi which can be found in all 4 ventricles (therefore it is correct that they are produced in the lateral, 3rd and 4th ventricles but this is SBA!).

Choroid Plexi are plexuses of capillaries which reside in the roof of the ventricles and they are basically releasing plasma into the brain from the capillaries (it isn't exactly the same but it's a good way of thinking about it) due to the fact blood cells and proteins cannot get through the capillary walls.

 

CSF is produced in all the ventricles however they are first produced in the lateral ventricles, they then travel to the 3rd Ventricle through the interventricular foramen. From here they then pass into the 4th Ventricle via the CEREBRAL AQUEDUCT. CSF then has two options, it can move down into the central canal of the spinal cord or it can pass up and around the brain in the subarachnoid space.

CSF is then collected and removed by the sinuses in the Meninges of the brain or by blood vessels at the bottom of the spinal cord.

 

Hope that helps! Here's a good video on the topic, which is where all the previous information came from, so if it's wrong blame her! - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GgRJnWBnq8o

Question: The trochlear nerve (CN IV) innervates only one muscle. What is this muscle?
Explanation: The trochlear nerve is purely somatic in function. It innervates the superior oblique muscle which depresses and intorts the eyeball causing the person to look down and in.

Question: What type of collagen is found in bone, skin, tendon, ligaments, cornea?
Explanation: About 15 kinds of collagen are known. Type I is the most common - 90% of all collagens are type I. This type is found in bone, skin, tendon, ligaments, cornea etc. Types I, II, III, V and IX are fibrillar, which means that the protein chains assemble into fibrils, 10-300nm in diameter. Types V & VI form networks in the basal lamina. Type VI helps to anchor basal lamina of skin to underlying connective tissue.

Question: What ion does the Cytochrome P450 enzyme (CYP) have as its catalytic site?

Question: What type of glial cell are you most likely to see in the CNS?
Explanation:
Glial Cells are cells that surround neurones providing them support and insulation. The only two examples in this question are Schwaan Cells and Oligodendrocytes.

Schwaan cells are the glial cells that are typically seen in the Peripheral Nervous System (PNS). 

Oligodendrocytes are the glial cells typically seen in the Central Nervous System (CNS).

Macrophages and Monocytes are leukocytes used in immunity and infection control. Pacinian corpuscles are mechanoreceptors responding to vibration and pressure.

-FYI other examples of glial cells are astrocytes, ependymal cells, microglia and satellite cells.

Question: How does the painkiller "Lignocaine" work?
Explanation: some painkillers work on the idea of threshold. lignocaine, a tropical drug, increases threshold and thus prevents many action potentials occurring. It’s thought to block voltage gated Na+ channels which are required to depolarise the cell more so. (normal Na+ channels do first bit to threshold, once threshold is reached it opens up voltage gated calcium ion channels, if lignocaine used then these channels won't open and an action potential won't occur, hence lack of sensation of pain!)

ATP--> ADP + Pi 

note ATP is the most widely used energy carrier in the body.

Question:
A 33yr old patient is about to embark on a trip through the Sahara desert, he wants to survive on foods not containing glucose but is adamant that he wants his body to produce Acetyl CoA to generate energy. 

 

How else, other than by using glucose, can the body produce acetyl- CoA?
Explanation:
Although this is a very specific question it tests for a high level understanding as to what and where exactly Acetyl-CoA arises from and is used for. 

 

entry to the TCA cycle is via acetyl CoA which is formed from pyruvate (the end point of glycolysis) in the link reaction,
Acetyl-CoA can also come from fatty acid breakdown or from the carbon skeletons of amino acids. This is key in times of fasting or low glucose as the body must generate energy somehow.

Question: A 12yr old patient is found to have a defective gene coding for the enzyme used to convert pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, what is the name of this enzyme?
Explanation: pyruvate dehydrogenase (PDH) is the enzyme required to convert pyruvate to acetyl CoA, it’s inhibited directly by high levels of CoA and NADH and indirectly by ATP via activate of PDH kinase which phosphorylates PDH and inactivates it.

Question: What is not a sensory supply of the mandibular nerve?
OptionA: mucous membranes and floor of the oral cavity
OptionD: lower molar, incisor and canine teeth and the associated ganglia
Explanation:
Sensory supply of the mandibular nerve:

- mucous membranes and the floor of the oral cavity

- external ear

- lower lip

- chin

- anterior 2/3rd of the tongue (only general sensation)

- lower molar, incisor and canine teeth and the associated gingiva

 

Motor supply of the mandibular nerve:

- Muscles of mastication

- Anterior belly of the digastric and mylohyoid muscles

- Tensor veli palatini

- tensor tympani

Question: Fat and cholesterol in the GI tract are assembled to form...
Explanation:
Chylomicrons carry triglycerides from the intestines to liver, skeletal muscle and adipose tissue.

VLDLs carry newly synthesised triglycerides from the liver to adipose tissue.

IDL and intermediate between VLDL and LDL.

LDL a 'bad cholesterol' that carries cholesterol from the liver to cells of the body.

HDL a 'good cholesterol' that collects cholesterol and returns it to the liver.

Question: Which receptor becomes activated when there is too much cholesterol in the peripheral tissue?
Explanation:
The ABCA1 receptor is activated in the reverse cholesterol pathway. HDL reacts with this receptor and collects cholesterol returning it to the liver.


HMG-CoA is a molecule that is converted into mevalonic acid in cholesterol production. It is not a receptor.

 

Apolipoprotein E (ApoE) is a class of apolipoprotein found in the chylomicron and Intermediate-density lipoprotein (IDLs) that is essential for the normal catabolism of triglyceride-rich lipoprotein constituents. It is not a receptor.

 

The LDL receptors are a cell-surface receptor that mediates the endocytosis of LDL cholesterol.

Question: Hepatic lipase acts on which type of cholesterol?
Explanation: Hepatic lipase acts on IDLs and breaks them down to form LDLs to transport the left over cholesterol to the muscle tissue. More information at: http://geekymedics.com/cholesterol-metabolism/

Question: Which of these cytokines activates Natural Killer (NK) cells?
Explanation:
IL-12 activates NK cells

 

IL-1 beta activates the vascular endothelium and activates lymphocytes as well as producing IL-6

 

IL-6 works systemically by inducing fever and inducing acute-phase protein production by hepatocytes

 

IL-8 (or CXCL8) is a chemotactic factor - it recruits neutrophils and basophils to the site of infection

 

TNF alpha activates the vascular endothelium and increases vascular permeability (makes it leaky) - allows complement entry and fluid drainage to lymph nodes

Question: Bile secretion has two mechanisms, what are they?

Bile secretion has two mechanisms

– depends on rate of bile acid return


• BAI -bile acid independent 2

Submandibular and sublingual glands are innervated by the facial nerve, or specifically the corda tympani nerve via submandibular ganglion.

Question: During which phase of fracture repair are chemokines released?
Explanation: The four phases of fracture repair are inflammation, soft callus, hard callus and remodelling. The inflammation phase starts soon after a fracture occurs and begins with haematoma formation at the injury site. Macrophages and inflammatory leukocyte a move into the damaged area to remove some of the debris and they produce pro-inflammatory chemiokines that initiate healing.
Tags: Case 1, Haematology, inflammatory response to injury

Question: A patient comes into your clinic with what you believe to be suspected hyperbilirubinemia. You do a blood test and urine test to investigate further. What are the results most likely to be if it is post-hepatic due to cholestasis?
OptionA: AST raised, ALT raised, in urine no conjugated bilirubin and raised plasma levels of unconjugated bilirubin
OptionB: ALT raised, ALT slightly raised, urine conjugated bilirubin and urobilinogen raised
OptionC: ALP raised, ALT slightly raised, raised GGT and no urine urobilinogen
Explanation:
A- These are the results you would expect from hepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia as the conjugating enzyme is lacking. This means there is an increase of unconjugated bilirubin in the plasma

 

B- These are the results you would expect from Hepatic conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia as it is caused by leakage of bile from the hepatocytes or biliary system

 

C- CORRECT! If there is a complete blockage this will result in no urine urobilinogen

 

D- The results expected from pre-hepatic hyperbilirubinaemia as liver function remains normal

Question: What organelle does Tay-Sachs disease affect?
Explanation: In Tay-Sachs disease, gangliosides taken up into the lysosomes are not degraded. This is because the sufferers lacks the enzyme beta-hexosaminidase A which is responsible for the breakdown of gangliosides derived from recycled plasma membrane. The lysosomes then accumulate lipid and become swollen.
Tags: PCS Unit 1, Cell structure, Cellular biology

Question: What is the method of action of botulinum toxin, which is commonly known as 'Botox'?
OptionA: Inhibits Myosin Light Chain Kinase to prevent muscle contraction
OptionB: Inhibits the production of ATP to supply the effected muscles
OptionC: Activates the Gi alpha subunit of a GPCR causing a reduction in intracellular cAMP
OptionD: Acts as an analgaesic through inhibition of A-delta nerve fibers
OptionE: Breaks down the SNARE complex to prevent acetylcholine release
Explanation:
The light chain (there's a heavy and a light chain) of botulinum toxin activates by breaking down the SNARE complex.

The SNARE complex is used to allow neurotransmitter-containing vesicles to fuse to the pre-synaptic membrane and release their neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft. Usually the v-SNARE on the vesicle membrane fuses with the t-SNARE on the presynaptic membrane to cause fusion, however this is prevented due to their breakdown by botulinum.

The release of acetylcholine leads to muscle contraction, therefore when botox is used as a cosmetic, this gives the associated smooth look. This is known as flacid paralysis. 

SNARE complexes where quite a difficult concept to grasp (probably because they where in the last small group session before christmas!) so here's a couple of good videos to help out! 

Neurotransmitter release and SNARE complexes :- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dxFLN2GP7M0

Botulinum toxin MOA (first half):- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2Dr929zjY4

Question: The risk of a healthy woman having a stroke is 1 in 200,000. The risk of a healthy woman on the combined contraceptive pill having a stroke is 1 in 125,000, what is the relative risk?
Explanation:
Relative risk is the higher risk over the lower risk

It can be misleading because 1 in 125,000 seems like a lower fraction than 1 in 200,000 because of the second number

Question: The autoimmune condition Pemphigus causes painful blisters on the skin and in the mouth. It is caused by the production of antibodies to what cell-cell junctions?
Explanation:
The correct answer is desmosomes. These are cell-cell junctions that hold adjacent cells together strongly.

Adherens Junctions also hold two adjacent cell membranes together, but to our knowledge are not associated with pephigus.

Hemidesomosomes hold cells onto the basement membrane.

Gap junctions are a method of communication between adjacent cells through little 'windows' in the membrane.

Tight Junctions are areas where two cells are held extremely close together with the assistance of claudin proteins.
Tags: PCS Unit 1, Pathology, Cell structure, Cellular biology

Question: What is the function of atrial natriuretic peptide in the kidney?
OptionA: Increase NaCl and H2O reabsorption and increase K+ secretion
OptionD: Increase NaCl and H2O reabsorption and increase H+ secretion
Explanation:
Atrial natriuretic peptide is responsible for decreasing NaCl reabsorption in the DCT and collecting duct.

 

Increase NaCl and H2O reabsorption and increase K+ secretion- This is the function of aldosterone

Increase H20 reabsorption- This is the function of ADH

Increase NaCl and H2O reabsorption and increase H+ secretion- This is the function of angiotensin II

Decrease PO4 reabsorption, increase Ca reabsorption- This is the function of parathyroid hormone

Question: Which of these conditions does not occur during the inflammatory response?

Explanation: Antigens can be produced by the body too.

Question: A new drug has been shown to influence instances of sudden cardiac death in people with Coronary syndrome. Of people on the drug, 1 in 20 of them suffer sudden cardiac death, compared to 1 in 5 of those not on the drug. What is the 'number needed to treat' for this drug (to the nearest whole patient)?
Explanation:
•NNT (Number needed to treat) is the number of people you need to give a drug before you have prevented a bad occurrence (In this case sudden cardiac death) in 1 of them.

 

•NNT (Number needed to treat) =1/ARD(Absolute Risk Difference)

 

•Absolute risk = Lower risk - Higher risk

 

Note: NNH (Number needed to harm) works exactly the same but with something bad rather than good, for example if the drug had a harmful side effect that occurred it calculates how many people can take the drug without experiencing the side effect.
Tags: Case 4, PCS unit 2, PCS unit 2 Heart, Pharmacology, Physiology

Question: During inflammation, vascular changes occur. In the blood vessels margination happens (where WBCs come into contact with the endothelial cells), the transmembrane protein(s) that allow(s) firm adhesion of the WBCs to the blood vessel wall is/are...
Explanation:
Beta 1 and Beta 2 integrins (integrins are transmembrane proteins) allow firm adhesion of WBCs to the endothelial cells of the wall of the blood vessel

(CAMs and integrins can combine to make the WBC completely immobile to help it come out of the blood vessel)

Question: How do Prostaglandins prevent the release of H+ into the stomach?
OptionA: Activates the Gs alpha subunit, activating Adenyl Cyclase and Protein Kinase A
OptionB: Activates the Gs alpha subunit, inhibiting Adenyl Cyclase and Protein Kinase A
OptionC: Activates the Gi alpha subunit, inhibiting Adenyl Cyclase and Protein Kinase A
OptionD: Activates the Gi subunit, activating Adenyl Cyclase and Protein Kinase A
OptionE: Activates the Gq subunit, activating Phospholipase C which cleaves PIP2 into DAG and IP3, activating Protein Kinase C
Explanation:
Prostaglandins bind to a GPCR receptor activating the alpha subunit - Gi. This Gi alpha subunit inhibits the actions of Adenyl Cyclase, meaning it cannot generate cAMP from ATP. As there is no cAMP, Protein Kinase A cannot be activated. Protein Kinase A is the enzyme that phosphorylates the H+/K+ antiporter which pumps H+ into the stomach.

There are 3 main types of alpha subunits:-

  • Gs = Stimulates Adenyl Cyclase (easy so remember because its Gs which stimulates adenyl cyclase)
  • Gi = Inhibits Adenyl Cyclase (again Gi = inhibits)
  • Gq = Activates Phospholipase C

Here's some helpful videos:-

- Gs activating the cAMP pathway (conversely Gi acts by inhibiting this pathway) = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z1QEirj1q7g

- Gq activating the PIP2 - DAG, IP3 pathway = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2CixTEYdCro

 

Takes a while to get your head around but a lot of other topics make much more sense when you have got it!

Question: Which of the following can be administrated to induce labour?
Explanation:
Gemeprost is an abortifacient (PGE1 analogue)

 

Dinoprost is a PG analogue. PG analogues are used to induce uterine contractions as uterine muscle's sensitivity to PGs increases through pregnancy (same applies for Misoprostol) 

-Oxytocin can also be given to induce labour through slow IV infusion

 

Mifepristone - another abortifacient. It's a progesterone receptor antagonist therefore essentially stops prog from doing what it's supposed to i.e. maintain endometrium. Therefore without a suitable environment can no longer maintain foetus

 

Spironolactone - anti-androgenic drug (given to treat gonadotropin independent precocious puberty)

Question: Hypogonatrophic hypogonadism is a cause of delayed puberty. Which of the following syndromes is an example of this and is due to a defect on chromosome 15?
Explanation:
Turner syndrome  causes delayed puberty BUT is an example of hypergonadotropic hypogonadism. Affects females. Monosomy X/1 X chromosome

Klinefelter syndrome causes delayed puberty BUT like Turner synd is also hypergonadotropic hypogonadism. Affects males. Extra copy of X chromosome

Kallmans syndrome is correct in that it is an example of hypogonatropic hypogonadism BUT it is not related to chromosome 15. It is usually X-linked and is due to a mutation in KAL1 gene. also causes anosmia.

Prader-Willi syndrome is the correct answer

McCune-Albright syndrome causes precocious puberty- 3 affects = 1) Endocrine hormone excess causing early puberty 2)Polyostotic fibrous dysplasia 3)unilateral cafe au lait spots on skin

Question: PYY is an anorexigenic. Where is its key release site?
OptionC: L-cells of mucosa of ileum and colon
Explanation:
Adipose cells -> secrete leptin which inhibits hunger like PYY

Fundus of stomach -> secretes ghrelin which stimulates appetite (orexigenic)

L-cells of mucosa of ileum and colon  -> CORRECT ANSWER; secrete PYY which inhibits hunger. It also decreases gastric motility

I cells of duodenum -> secrete CCK which inhibits hunger by delaying emptying of stomach

Hypothalamus -> secretes orexin in response to Ghrelin and hypoglycaemia

Question: what would a decrease in afferent tone do to the GFR in the glomeruli?
Explanation: An increase in the afferent tone will mean that blood flow into the glomerulus increases so that the glomerular filtration rate will increase.

Question: Which pathway of the complement system is activated by antibodies?
Explanation: The classical pathway is initiated when an antibody binds to a pathogen, which is recognised by C1. This leads to the lysis of C3 by C3 convertase (the start of the terminal pathway).

Question: Which of these is correct, with regard to the movement of K+ and Na+ across the axon cell membrane?
OptionA: The ATP pump transports 2 K+ into the cell for every 3 Na+ out of the cell. The membrane is readily permeable to Na+, but poorly permeable to K+.
OptionB: The ATP pump transports 3 K+ into the cell for every 2 Na+ out of the cell. The membrane is readily permeable to K+, but poorly permeable to Na+.
OptionC: The ATP pump transports 2 K+ into the cell for every 3 Na+ out of the cell. The membrane is readily permeable to K+, but poorly permeable to Na+.
OptionD: The ATP pump transports 3 K+ into the cell for every 2 Na+ out of the cell. The membrane is readily permeable to Na+, but poorly permeable to K+.
OptionE: The ATP pump transports 2 K+ into the cell for every 3 Na+ out of the cell. The membrane is poorly permeable to K+, but impermeable to Na+.
Explanation:
The Na+/K+ ATPase pump exchanges 2 K+ in for every 3 Na+ out, helping to create an electrochemical gradient.

 

The membrane is readily permeable to K+ and Cl-, poorly permeable to Na+, and impermeable to A- (large organic anions such as proteins).

 

This was covered in Marisol's lecture on membrane potentials in PCS1.

Question: During pre-drinks, Oliver had too many sambuca shots and fell off the table he was dancing on. After being rushed to A&E (after yet another sambuca shot to steady the nerves), the doctor performed a Babinski test. What would a positive Babinski sign be representative of?
What is the role of the enzyme α1-antitrypsin in the lungs?
OptionA: Provides an antimicrobial effect in the alveoli
OptionB: Inhibits the breakdown of elastic tissue by destructive proteases in the lung
OptionC: Allows the exchange of gases at the meeting point of the alveoli and capillaries
OptionD: Causes the production of mucus in goblet cells
OptionE: Activates a Calcium channel in order to cause bronchoconstriction
Explanation:
Lung secretions contain a number of enzymes called antiproteases, α1-antitrypsin is one of the most important. They break down the destructive proteases that are produced in the lung by dead bacteria, macrophages and neutrophils. 

For example when cigarette smoke is inhaled there is an increase in leucocytes in the lung. These leucocytes produce elastase that attack the elastic tissue of the lungs. 

However this process is inhibited by α1-antitrypsin. If there is a defect in this enzyme i.e through genetic disposition or through oxygen radicals from cigarette smoke inhibiting them, then this can lead to loss of elastic tissue and emphysema.

 

Quite a difficult question and may not be relevant however it is interesting and useful to know. There is a good amount of crucial and extra information in the 'Crash Course -Respiratory System' book which is an easy to read and understand textbook available as an e-book.

Question: What happenes to the electron transport chain if you take Amytal?
OptionB: FADH2 Is still able to produce ATP through complex 2,3,4 and 5
OptionC: NADH is still able to produce ATP through complex 1,3,4 and 5
OptionE: NADH is still able to produce ATP through complex 2,3,4 and 5
Explanation: amytal blocks ECT between complex 1 and cytochrome Q10 so NADH can't produce ATP but FADH2 can. Refer to lecture releasing energy from food using oxygen for info

Question: What fibrous tissue layer covers a skeletal muscle fibre?
Explanation:
In a muscle epimysium sheaths the whole muscle and helps transfer force into the tendon of the muscle, the perimysium covers the fascicles which are bundles of individual muscle fibers, and ENDOMYSIUM covers individual muscle fibres. The epimysium and endomysium also contain nerve fibres and blood vessels.

 

 

In a nerve the nerve fibre is covered in a layer known as the epineurium, there are bundles of axons which are surrounded by a layer called the perineurium, and the individual axons are sheathed by the endoneurium. The blood vessels that supply nerve fibres run through the centre of the nerve.

Question: Apolipoproteins are proteins which bind to lipids to form lipoproteins. Their main functions are to transport lipids and maintain the structural integrity of lipoproteins. Which of the following is a receptor ligand for HDLs (High density lipoproteins)?
Explanation:
Apo B48 is a receptor ligand for chylomicrons.

Apo B100 is a receptor ligand for LDLs.

For all Apo B, high levels are related to heart disease.

Apo A1 is the correct answer because it is a receptor ligand for HDLs. Deficiency of this apolipoprotein is linked to HDL deficiency and can cause diseases such as Tangiers disease (characterised by discolouration of organs).

Apo C2 is a lipoprotein lipase that is found in capillaries. It liberates fatty acids and triglycerides from chylomicrons. Deficiency of this can lead to hyperlipoproteinaemia and hypertriglyceridaemia.

Apo E is involved in receptor recognition of IDLP (intermediate density lipoproteins). It is essential for catabolism of triglycerides.

Question: In One Fish, Two Fish, Blowfish, Blue Fish (the 24th episode of The Simpsons), Homer consumes toxic Fugu at The Happy Sumo, a Japanese restaurant. Fugu is the Japanese word for pufferfish, which contains the toxin TTX (tetradotoxin). What is its mechanism of action?
OptionA: It binds to the extracellular side of voltage-gated K+ channels.
OptionB: It binds to postsynaptic nicotinic acetylcholine receptors.
OptionC: It binds to the extracellular side of voltage-gated Na+ channels.
OptionD: It promotes the reuptake of acetylcholine across the presynaptic membrane.
OptionE: It binds to the extracellular side of voltage-gated Na+ and voltage-gated K+ channels.
Explanation:
It binds to the extracellular side of voltage-gated Na+ channels, preventing action potentials from being generated or propagated. Paralysis of the diaphragm results in respiratory failure, which is usually the cause of death.

 

Fortunately Homer survived, and has since appeared in 569 further episodes of The Simpsons!

 

(This was taught in PCS1, during the plenary on Action Potentials).
Tags: Action Potentials, Membrane potentials, Neuroscience, PCS Unit 1, Pharmacology

Question:
Ananth is a strong, independent 36 year old woman, who presents at your clinic with breathlessness and a dry cough. She has no smoking history. And on examination, you hear fine inspiratory crackles. You performed a spirometry test on her and the results are:

 

FVC= 74% of expected value

FEV1= 73% of expected value

FEV1:FVC = 83% 

 

What does these results show?
Explanation:
Restrictive: FVC and FEV1 both decrease by the same amount. Hence, the FEV1:FVC ratio stays the same. 

Obstructive: FEV1 decreases. FVC stays the same. FEV1:FVC decreases.

What is the most likely diagnosis?
Explanation: Unexplained weight loss and blood in sputum are red flag symptoms for cancer.

Question: Which of the following type of epithelium exists in the terminal bronchioles?
Explanation:
This picture shows a Terminal bronchiole (TB in the diagram). Note that this is at a lower magnification than the three pictures above.This is the last part of the conducting portion of the respiratory system, and has the smallest diameter of all (less than 1mm).

There is no cartilage, or glands, some smooth muscle is still present, there are no goblet cells. The epithelium is simple ciliated cuboidal.

Question: Cells that present a Major Histocompatibility Complex I (MHC I) do so to indicate that they are infected. To what immune cells do they present this information to, in order to attempt to rid the pathogen?
Explanation:
CD8+ T-cells are killer T-Cells.

When a cell is infected they present broken down proteins from the pathogen on their cell surface. This can either be as a MHC I or a MHC II.

MHC I presents to CD8+ cells in order to cause them to either become active cytotoxic T-cells which kill the infected cells, or they become active CD4+ helper T-cells which secrete antibodies to the infected cell.

 

MHC II presents to CD4+ cells causing them to either bind to macrophages initiating cytokine release, or bind to B-cells to secrete antibodies.

Question: When performing a clinical examination, what are the 4 key steps in any examination, and what is the suggested order?
Explanation:
The order is:-

 

-Inspection (look)

-Palpation (feel)

-Percussion (listen for dullness or resonance) 

-Auscultation (use the stethoscope to listen for internal sounds)

 

-(Although this obviously isn't set in stone! Different physicians may do it in a different order and if you forget one step your medical career probably isn't over!)

 

Ideas, concerns, expectations, effects on life (ICEE) is a communication technique used to ensure patients opinions and thoughts are taken into consideration during a history taking/consultation.

Stop, look listen, live is the green cross code. Stay safe kids.

Question: An exhausted junior doctor is about to do his ward rounds in the 117th hour of his shift in the new and improved 7 day a week NHS. Before doing so he drinks a cup of black coffee and an energy drink to ensure that he is fully awake, to avoid making a mistake due to tiredness. After doing so he notices that his heart rate increases drastically. His colleague suggests this is due to the caffeine in the drinks. How does caffeine have this effect?
OptionC: It activates the enzyme Myosin Light-Chain Kinase
Explanation: Caffeine is a phosphodiesterase inhibitor, which is the enzyme that breaks down cAMP. Therefore leading to more cAMP and therefore more Calcium ions in the cardiac muscle due to activation of Protein Kinase A and therefore we see more cross-bridge formation and more contractions of heart muscle.

Question: Hemidesmosomes look similar to desmosomes but differ in function and content. Transmembrane proteins in hemidesmosomes are:
Explanation:
Hemidesmosomes connect basal surface of epithelial cells to underlying basal lamina via intermediate filaments.

 

Cadherins (specifically desmoglein and desmocollin) are transmembrane proteins found in desmosomes.

Connexins are protein molecules which group together to form connexons, which when aligned form gap junctions.

Integrins are transmembrane proteins found in hemidesmosomes.

Keratin forms the intermediate filaments found in desmosomes of the skin.

Actin joins up adherens junctions by forming a marginal band.
Tags: Biochemistry, PCS Unit 1, Histology, cytoskeleton, Cell structure

Question: Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of cartilage?
Explanation: Cartilage is slow to repair since it is avascular. Must rely on chondrocytes to produce cartilagenous matrix.
Tags: PCS Unit 1, Cell Signaling, Cell structure

Question: The carnitine shuttle is the rate limiting step of beta oxidation. It is made up of 3 parts; CPT-1, a translocase protein and CPT-2. What inhibits this step and which part does it act on?
OptionA: Inhibited by Acyl CoA which acts on CPT-1
OptionB: Inhibited by Malonyl CoA which acts on CPT-1
OptionC: Inhibited by Malonyl CoA which acts on CPT-2
OptionD: Inhibited by Acyl CoA which acts on the translocate protein
OptionE: Inhibited by Malonyl CoA which acts on the translocase protein
Explanation:
The carnitine shuttle is inhibited by malonyl coA, whereas it is activated by Acyl coA which is the substrate.

The enzyme CPT-1 is specifically inhibited which is the first committed step.

Andrew Shore's lecture - Mobilising energy stores; PCS 3 

 

EXTRA INFO

 

Mutations are common in CPT1 and CPT2 but rare in the translocase enzyme - implications of this are important because if the carnitine shuttle isn't working then fatty acids can no longer be used a substitute energy source when glucose levels are low

 

Also, lipogenesis/FA synthesis switches OFF fatty acid breakdown...

  •          therefore if there is an insulin signal, lipogenesis increases which increases Mal CoA levels THEREFORE a greater inhibitory effect on the carnitine shuttle --> (this is beneficial because when glucose levels are high, there is no need to be using up fat stores so inhibition of beta oxidation is achieved by increasing MalCoA levels)
  •         If there is a glucagon signal however, the opposite happens; lipogenesis decreases (since lipolysis increases). This decreases levels of Mal CoA so less inhibition of the shuttle -->  (this is beneficial because when in glucose levels are low, we need an alternative energy source i.e fats so by decreasing MalCoA you can have higher activity of beta oxidation and hence utilising fats as an energy source more)

Question: A patient suffering from chronic myeloid leukaemia has been found to carry the 'Philadelphia Chromosome'. Which of the following best describes the abnormality....
OptionD: Deletion of the short arm on chromosome 22
OptionE: Deletion of the short arm on chromosome 9
Explanation:
a) this is wrong because it is not a robertsonian translocation. A robertsonian translocation involves the fusion between long arms of acrocentric chromosomes with the loss of the short arms

 

b) CORRECT - chromosome 9 carries the BCR gene and chromosome 22 carries c-ABL protooncogene(kinase). when these undergo reciprocal translocation, the BCR-ABL fusion protein becomes 'over-active' and no longer regulated. This drives cell into division.

 

c) Non-disjunction leads to numerical abnormalities rather than structural (Robertsonian translocation, Reciprocal translocation and deletions are all structural abnormalities). An example of Non-disjunction is in Down Syndrome/Trisomy 21 leading to disomic gametes (gametes with 2 copies of ch21). However Robertsonian translocation can also lead to Down syndrome

Also it wouldn't make sense in this case as non-disjunction occurs during meiosis and therefore chromosome 9 and 22 wouldn't line up together in the first place as they are not homologous.

 

 

PCS 3; Chromosome abnormalities lecture

Question: an increase in which hormone (associated with a high BMI) can cause early onset of menarche?
Explanation:
Leptin is a hormone which is produced by adipocytes, and hence when young females have a higher BMI more leptin is secreted. 

once secreted it stimulates the hypothalamic pituitary axis to cause GnRH secretion and the increase in gonadotrophin hormones. 

This means the higher the females BMI, the more leptin is secreted and hence the earlier puberty could onset.

Question:
The tanner scale of puberty classifies the physical development that occurs during puberty. 

 

In a female, at what tanner stage would the breasts begin to bud and the areola begin to form?
Explanation:
Tanner 1 (prepubertal) Age <10 • No areola.
• No breast/budding breasts.
• No pubic hair.


Tanner 2 Age 10-11

• Breasts begins to bud, no separate contour.
• Small areola forms and widens.
• Small amount of long hair with slight pigmentation on the labia majora.


Tanner 3 Age 11-13

• Breasts become more elevated, yet no separate contour.
• Areolar continues to widen.
• Pubic hair becomes coarse and curly.

 

Tanner 4 Age 13-15

• Breast size increases.
• Areola and papilla form a secondary mound above breast level.
• Adult like hair which extends across the pubis.

 

Tanner 5 (adult/mature) Age 15+

• Breast reaches adult size.
• Areola returns to fit the contour of the surrounding breast.
• Papilla projects centrally.
• Pubic hair spreads to the medial thighs.

Question: A patient who has recently broken his ankle presents to A&E with breathlessness and pain in his upper back. You discover through testing that he is suffering a pulmonary embolism. What is the most likely Ventilation:Perfusion ratio in this patient?
Explanation:
When a patient suffers a pulmonary embolism, there is restricted blood flow (perfusion) to the alveoli for gas exchange however air flow (ventilation) is normal.

Therefore via the equation:

                                                     Ratio = Ventilation

                                                                 --------------

                                                                  Perfusion

 

The perfusion will be 0 due to no blood flow and the ratio can be infinitively high.

 

If there was restricted ventilation i.e through pneumonia then ventilation would be closer to 0 leaving a ratio of close to 0.

A ratio of 1 is healthy.

You cannot get a ratio any lower than 0.

Question: Which of the following statements, about the physiology of respiration, is correct:
OptionA: Inspiration occurs passively, due to relaxation of the diaphragm, which increases intrathoracic volume.
OptionB: Normal expiration involves contraction of the rectus abdominis muscle and internal intercostal muscles.
OptionD: Normal expiration is a largely passive process, due to the relaxation of the diaphragm and external intercostal muscles.
OptionE: Inspiration is due to the peristaltic waves of contraction of smooth muscle in the trachea and primary bronchi, which push pockets of air downward into the lung.
Explanation:
Normal Inspiration is an active process, due to contraction of the diaphragm (contraction causes it to flatten) and the external intercostal muscles, which lift the thoracic cage upwards and outwards. This increases intrathoracic volume. If inspiration is forced, accessory muscles such as the sternocleidomastoid, scalene muscles, serratus anterior and pectoralis minor may also contract.

 

Expiration is largely passive, and is due to the relaxation of the muscles which were previously contracted during inspiration: the diaphragm returns to being largely curved upwards and the ribs return down and in towards their original position. This reduces the volume within the thorax. If expiration is forced, accessory muscles such as the rectus abdominis, transversus thoracis, internal oblique and internal intercostals will contract.

 

Option E is totally made up to throw you, but I'm sure you knew this. Peristalsis occurs along the GI tract, not in the trachea!
Tags: Anatomy, Respiratory system, Case 5, PCS unit 2, Physiology

Question: What does Virchow's Triad state, and to what disease process might it's principles apply?
OptionA:
That thrombosis occurs due to alteration in:

The integrity of the vessel wall

The composition of the blood to render it hyper-coagulative

Blood flow.

 

Myocardial Infarction caused by a ruptured atherosclerotic plaque.
OptionB:
That thrombosis occurs due to alteration in:

The integrity of the vessel wall;

The composition of the blood to render it hypo-coagulative;

Blood flow.

 

Right-sided heart failure.
OptionC:
That thrombosis occurs due to alteration in:

The integrity of the vessel wall;

The composition of the blood to render it hyper-coagulative;

Increased blood flow.

 

Left-sided heart failure.
OptionD:
That thrombosis occurs due to alteration in:

The integrity of the coagulation cascade;

The composition of the blood to render it hyper-coagulative;

Blood flow.

 

Aneurysms.
OptionE:
That thrombosis occurs due to increases in:

The integrity of the vessel wall;

The composition of the blood to render it hyper-coagulative;

Blood flow.

 

Neisseria infections.
Explanation:
Wierkoff's Triad states that:

That thrombosis occurs due to alteration in:

The integrity of the vessel wall

The composition of the blood to render it hyper-coagulative

Blood flow.

 

Myocardial Infarctions, when a result of a ruptured plaque, are a classic example of a disease process that results in a change of the three tenets in Wierkoff's Triad. The integrity of the vessel wall has been compromised by the rupture of the plaque; the composition of the blood has been altered by exposure to the thrombogenic contents of the plaque and there is reduced blood flow due to the narrowing caused by the plaque.
Tags: Blood Vessels, Cardiology, Case 5, Haematology, Clinical Significance

Question: Which of the following is the CORRECT way that Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) flows through the brain?
OptionA:
CSF is secreted by choroid plexus in each lateral ventricle -> CSF flows through interventricular foramina into the 3rd ventricles -> CSF flows down cerebral aqueduct to 4th ventricle -> CSF flows out one lateral aperture and two medial apertures -> CSF fills subarachnoid space and bathes external surfaces of brain and spinal cord

 

At arachnoid villi, CSF is reabsorbed into venous blood of dural venous sinuses
OptionB:
CSF is secreted by choroid plexus in each lateral ventricle -> CSF flows through interventricular foramina into the 3rd ventricles -> CSF flows down cerebral aqueduct to 4th ventricle -> CSF flows out two lateral apertures and one medial aperture -> CSF fills pia mater and bathes external surfaces of brain and spinal cord

 

At arachnoid villi, CSF is reabsorbed into venous blood of dural venous sinuses
OptionC:
CSF is secreted by choroid plexus in each anterior ventricle -> CSF flows through interventricular foramina into the 4th ventricles -> CSF flows down cerebral aqueduct to 3rd ventricle -> CSF flows out two lateral apertures and one medial aperture -> CSF fills subarachnoid space and bathes external surfaces of brain and spinal cord

 

At arachnoid villi, CSF is reabsorbed into venous blood of dural venous sinuses
OptionD:
CSF is secreted by choroid plexus in each lateral ventricle -> CSF flows through interventricular foramina into the 3rd ventricles -> CSF flows down cerebral aqueduct to 4th ventricle -> CSF flows out two lateral apertures and one medial aperture -> CSF fills subarachnoid space and bathes external surfaces of brain and spinal cord

 

At arachnoid villi, CSF is reabsorbed into venous blood of dural venous sinuses
OptionE:
CSF is secreted by choroid plexus in each posterior ventricle -> CSF flows through interventricular foramina into the 3rd ventricles -> CSF flows down cerebral aqueduct to 4th ventricle -> CSF flows out two lateral apertures and two medial apertures -> CSF fills subarachnoid space and bathes external surfaces of brain and spinal cord

 

At arachnoid villi, CSF is reabsorbed into venous blood of dural venous sinuses
Explanation: so D is the correct answer

Question: Dyneins and Kinesins are motor proteins associated with which cytoskeletal structure?
Explanation:
A) correct - dynes and kinesins are microtubule-associated motor proteins - the use ATP hydrolysis to move across microtubules

main protein is tubulin of which there is alpha and n

primary involved in transporting vesicles inside cells 

B) Microfilaments - main protein is actin and its role is gross movement of the cell e.g cell division

C) Intermediate filaments - main protein is lamin and primary function is structural support (they act like mattress springs)

D) Desmosomes - these are not cytoskeletal structures, they are cell-to-cell junctions connecting neighbouring cells via intermediate filaments 

E) Hemidesmosomes - these are not cytoskeletal structures, they are cell-to-cell junctions connecting intermediate filaments to basal lamina

Question:
A drug to be given intravenously to a patient is of concentration 235µg/mL.

Express this concentration as a 'percentage'.
Explanation:
We assume 1mL of liquid = 1g of liquid (unless stated otherwise)

therefore:

 

                             235µg/mL = 235µg in 1g

 

(to work out % units

need to be the same

soconvert  µg into g)            = 235x10^-6g in 1g

 

                                          % = (235x10^-6)/1  x100

   

                                              = 0.0235% solution

Question:
Where in the descending aorta does the following vessels branch off?

 

 - Coeliac Trunk

 - Superior Mesenteric Artery

 - Inferior Mesenteric Artery
OptionA:
Coeliac Trunk - T11
Superior Mesenteric Artery - T12
Inferior Mesenteric Artery - L1
OptionB:
Coeliac Trunk - T12
Superior Mesenteric Artery - L1
Inferior Mesenteric Artery - L5
OptionC:
Coeliac Trunk - L1
Superior Mesenteric Artery - L3
Inferior Mesenteric Artery - L5
OptionD:
Coeliac Trunk - T12
Superior Mesenteric Artery - L1 
Inferior Mesenteric Artery - L3
OptionE:
Coeliac Trunk - T12
Superior Mesenteric Artery - L1
Inferior Mesenteric Artery - L2
Explanation:
Coeliac Trunk - T12 --> gives off 3 branches: left gastric artery, splenic artery, common hepatic artery

 

Superior Mesenteric Artery - L1 --> Jejunal and illeal arteries, illeocolic artery, right colic artery, middle colic artery. (Basically supplies the midgut from the major duodenal papilla (of the duodenum) to the proximal 2/3 of the transverse colon)


Inferior Mesenteric Artery - L3 --> left colic artery, sigmoid artery and superior rectal artery. (So it supplies the hindgut from the distal 2/3rds of the transverse colon to the rectum).

 

Note: The stomach received its blood supply from all three branches off the coeliac trunk.

Peace MR.

Side note: There are two types of ACh receptors: Nicotinic and muscarinic ACh receptors. 

 

- ACh acts on nicotinic receptors in the autonomic ganglia (are GPCR)
- ACh acts on muscarinic receptors in the target tissues (are ligand-gated ion channels)

Question: Which best describes the receptors for sympathetic efferent neuron neurotransmitters?
OptionC:
Preganglionic: nicotinic
Postganglionic: alpha 1, alpha 2, beta 1, beta 2 adrenergic
OptionD:
Preganglionic: alpha 1, alpha 2, beta 1, beta 2 adrenergic 
Postganglionic: alpha 1, alpha 2, beta 1, beta 2 adrenergic
Explanation:
In sympathetic neurones, the preganglionic neurotransmitter is acetylcholine and the postganglionic neurotransmitter is usually adrenaline. Therefore usually, the preganglionic receptor is nicotinic, whereas the post ganglionic receptors are adrenergic.

In parasympathetic neurones, both the preganglionic and postganglionic neurotransmitters are acetylcholine and the corresponding receptors are nicotinic and muscarinic (option A).

Question:
You have 5mL ampoules of drug 'X'

Each ampoule contains 63mg of drug 'X'

You administer 7mg/mL of drug 'X' to a patient in a total volume of 45mL

How many drug ampoules and what diluting volume of normal saline did you use to make this solution?
Explanation:
1 ampoule of drug 'X' ( 5mL) contains 63mg of 'X'

 

The solution given to the patient contains 7mg/mL of 'X' in 45mL, therefore, total amount of 'X' in 45mL = 315mg

 

315/63 = 5 ...therefore you would need 5 ampoules of 'X' to have 315mg

 

5 ampoules of 'X' = 25mL 

 

45mL - 25mL = 20mL ...this remaining volume is the volume of normal saline that would have been added

Question: Oculomotor Nerve Palsy presents with which of the following appearances?
Explanation:
Lateral rectus and superior oblique are supplied by VI and IV respectively. Palsy of CNIII results in unopposed actions of lateral rectus and superior oblique therefore giving patients a 'down and out' appearance.

 

No medial displacement since medial rectus is supplied by CNIII

Question: A patient with Gilbert's or Crigler-Najjar syndromes carry a mutated form of a type of UGT's. These enzymes are used in Phase II of drug/toxin metabolism, specifically bilirubin in these cases. What is the main action of these enzymes with respect to bilirubin?

The answer is B = Conjugating a water soluble glucuronide to the drug/metabolite, as it conjugates bilirubin to allow it to be excreted via the faeces, in these syndromes - the mutated or deleted UGTA1 results in a build up of unconjugated bilirubin (hyperbilirubinaemia)

Question:
Mary decides to take advantage of the glorious weather and heads for a run. She's giving it absolute socks, and because she's an inquisitive med student she wonders how her body reacts to get more blood to her muscles.

 

What is the primary intrinsic blood vessel control mechanism that is causing increased blood flow (hyperaemia) here?
Explanation:
A - Autoregulation is occurring to avoid over-dilation: Membrane stretch in blood vessels activates stretch-activated Ca2+ cation channels resulting in vasoconstriction. It is not causing the increase in blood flow to her muscles though!

 

B - Active (or Metabolic) Hyperaemia - correct, as this is the intrinsic vasodilation reaction to increased metabolism (decreasing O2, increasing Co2 etc.) as a result of muscle usage

 

C - Capillaries do not exhibit any control as they have little to no smooth muscle, so they cannot dilate or constrict by muscle tone

 

D - Reactive Hyperaemia is a transient increase in blood flow following brief period of ischaemia and occlusion - hopefully not happening while she is exercising!

 

E - A bit of a mean answer to include as it is correct that if noradrenaline acts on beta-2 adrenoceptors in muscle it causes vasodilation. However it is an example of extrinsic control, not intrinsic as the question asks!

 

This question was created from the Case 4 Week 1 Physiology tutorial. Please refer to it if anything needs clarification!

Question:
you are an FY1 who has been called by a nurse to a patient who is unconscious on a nearby ward, and is thought to be in cardiac arrest.

Upon examination the patient has no pulse and the ECG shows a "flat line" as shown in right half of the image below.

 

what type of cardiac arrest is this patient experiencing and what would be the method of action to try and reestablish a normal heart rhythm?
Explanation:
There are 4 types of cardiac arrests, each of which appear differently on an ECG, and they can be divided into two categories:

 

 - SHOCKABLE WITH DEFIBRILLATOR:

     - Ventricular tachycardia: wide QRS complex seen with tachycardia.

     - Ventricular fibrillation: rapid (over 400bpm) erratic beating pattern. 

 

 - REQUIRE MANUAL LIFE SUPPORT:

     - Systole: no electrical activity is seen e.g. "flat line". this is a failure in electrical activity of the heart.

     - Pulse less electrical activity: normal ECG is seen yet no pulse is detected, this is a failure in cardiac output. 

 

STEMI is not a form of cardiac arrest, instead this is a form of myocardial infarction. STEMI can lead to a cardiac arrest if not treated quickly or correctly. Hence the answer to this question must be C - aystole (typical flat line ECG).
Tags: Cardiology, The Heart, Case 4, PCS unit 2 Heart

Question: Satellite cells are distributed between muscle fibres and the basement membrane. What is their function?
OptionC: Efficient repair of minor tears in muscle
Explanation: A minor tear of a muscle may be repaired by replacement of damaged cells with these satellite cells. However, major tears cannot utilise this mechanism of repair - larger lesions are repaired by fibrosis.

Question: What is housemaid's knee?
OptionA: The knee of someone who cleans houses for a living
OptionB: Swelling of the anterior side of the knee due to inflammation of the prepatella bursae.
OptionC: Swelling of the posterior side of the knee due to inflammation of the prepatella bursae.
OptionD: Swelling of the inferior side of the knee due to inflammation of the infrapatella bursae.
OptionE: Swelling of the superior side of the knee due to inflammation of the suprapatella bursae.
Explanation: Friction between the skin and the patella cause the prepatella bursa to become inflamed, producing a swelling on the anterior side of the knee. This is known as “housemaid’s knee”.

Question: What is clergyman's knee?
OptionA: Swelling of the knee due to the more than one bursae being inflamed, as a result of excess friction between the skin and the patella.
OptionB: Swelling of the knee due to friction between between the skin and anterior patella causing the prepatella to become inflamed.
OptionC: Swelling of the knee due to compression of the superior part of the knee causing the suprapatella to become inflammed.
OptionD: Swelling of the knee due to compression at the back of the knee causing the semimembranosus bursae to become inflammed.
OptionE: Swelling of the knee due to friction between the skin and tibia causing the infrapatella to become inflamed.
Explanation:
Friction between the skin and the patella cause the prepatella bursa to become inflamed, producing a swelling on the anterior side of the knee. This is known as “housemaid’s knee”.

 

Similarly, friction between the skin and tibia can cause the infrapatella bursa to become inflamed, resulting in what is known as “clergyman’s knee” (typically caused by clergymen kneeling on hard surfaces during prayer).

Question: Which one of the following statements regarding the circle of Willis is correct?
OptionA: It is the primary source of blood supply to the pons and medulla.
OptionC: It is the site where most of the cerebrospinal fluid is formed.
OptionD: The superior cerebellar artery arises from the circle of Willis.
OptionE: It surrounds the optic chiasm and the infundibulum of the pituitary.
Explanation: The circle of Willis is formed by the anastomosis of the branches of the internal carotid artery and  the terminal branches of the basilar artery. The arteries that form the circle of Willis include the anterior & posterior communicating arteries and posterior cerebral arteries. Vertebral and superior cerebellar arteries are not included in the circle of Willis hence does not supply blood to the pons and medulla. When the circle of Willis is patent (only in 20% of individuals), it supplies the hypothalamus, hypophysis, infundibulum, thalamus, caudate nucleus, putamen, internal capsule, globus pallidus, choroid plexus and temporal lobe. 70% of CSF is produced by choroid plexus in the lateral ventricles. [from Siegel and Sapru's Essential Neuroscience 3rd edition]

Question: A patient presents with visible drooping on one side of their face, inability to taste and increased sensitivity to sound. Which cranial nerve is most likely damaged?

Question: Which type of cells migrate to form the theca around a primary oocyte?
Explanation:
Granulosa cells- convert androgens to oestrogen in secondary oocytes, and after ovulation they secrete progesterone. Also known as follicular cells.

 

Follicular cells- another name for granulosa cells, though more often called follicular cells in the early stages of development.

 

Theca cells- MADE UP

 

Stromal cells- correct answer- in a primary oocyte, stream cells of the ovary migrate around the oocyte to form the theca capsule. When the oocyte develops into a secondary oocyte, the theca differentiates into two layers:

  • the theca interna (which are larger cells, produce follicular fluid, and have receptors for LH which produces a precursor that granulosa cells can use to produce oestrogen) 
  • theca externa- more fibrous layer and continuous with the stroma of the ovary

Pellucida cells-MADE UP

Question: The Hearing-Breuer reflex is an important reflex that prevents overinflation of the lungs. Which receptors bring this about?
Explanation:
The Hearing-Breuer reflex is via the vagus nerve and plays a protective role in preventing over-inflation of the lungs. It does this via decreasing inspiratory discharge and hence terminates inflation.

Question: Kieran (the puffy jacket man who's friends with Jorge who has ginger hair) was running to Dr Watson's lecture about hearing when a fly flew into his eye. He did not notice this and damage to the conjunctiva resulted. Upon examination by an F1 doctor, he was found to have a whitened sclera and a dilated pupil. What drug may he have taken prior to leaving taly for the lecture?
Explanation:
Cocaine is the only drug (in Dr Coffey practical) that has both a local anaesthetic and sympathomimetic effect. (It blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels and Noradrenaline re-uptake).

 

It also blocks serotonin re-uptake, which is why Kieran feels happy despite his trip to hospital.

 

It causes vasoconstriction of the blood vessels in the periphery such as the nose - so next time you see him, his may be missing.

Question: ABGs of a patient show that PaO2 is below 8kPa (hypoxaemia). You calculate the Aa gradient which seems to be significantly increased. You then decide to put the patient on high flow oxygen but no improvement is seen. What is the most likely cause for the patient's hypoxaemia?
Explanation:
All the listed above are causes of hypoxaemia but.....

 

A) Hypoventilation - it can't be this because Aa gradient would be normal (treated with NIV)

 

B) V/Q mismatch - yes this would show a high Aa gradient BUT if this was the cause then signs of improvement would be seen upon high flow oxygen 

  •      causes of V/Q mismatch include; COPD, pulmonary embolism, pneumonia

C) Diffusion problem - this would also show a high Aa gradient BUT again like V/Q mismatch, if this was the cause the patient would respond well to high flow oxygen

  • main cause of diffusion problem is fibrosis

D) Shunt; CORRECT> a shunt would cause a high Aa gradient but the patient would NOT show any signs of improvement upon high flow O2

  • main cause of shunting would be pulmonary oedema, ARDS
Tags: Lung Function, Lungs, Respiratory system, Case 5

Question:
After a heavy pre drinks session and a boogie on the cardiff legendary night out (flux) dance floor and a few to many magical orange VKs, Ellen has an 'evening of passion' with one of her exs Jakes rugby lads mates.

The correct answer is B 

 

Mifepristone and Misoprostol are the MEDICAL names of these drugs - these can only be used up to 12 weeks, as after other methods, often surgical need to be used instead. 

- Mifepristone works by inhibiting progesterone receptors - as progesterone is essential for maintaining pregnancy

** NOTE that hCG getting the corpus luteum to secrete progesterone for 8 weeks is necessary to maintain pregnancy - until the placenta takes over - mifepristone stops this from happening 

 

Misoprostol is a PGE1 analogue - it is a medication used to start labour - so contractions of the womb; it can either be taken orally, vaginally or placed under the tongue (quicker access to the blood stream) 

also used to help prevent stomach ulcers 

 

** UNRELATED SIDE NOTES ABOUT TAKING DRUGS UNDERNEATH THE TONGUE

- due to the composition of the tissue that lie on the underneath of the tongue, drugs are administered more quickly into the drug stream than via the GI route. However this principle works the SAME for alcohol too - so next time you are at flux, try taking a shot and holding the alcohol under your tongue for between 10-20 seconds - it will be absorbed by the blood stream quicker - making you drunk quicker - cheap and cheerful tactical fact. 

 

Oxytocin - induces labour by inducing uterine contractions

Melancortins - is used for erectile dysfunction

Question: Doris has had a new cochlear implant inserted. Unfortunately, she has found that she the implant is not working properly as she still cannot distinguish between different frequencies/pitches. What is the problem with the implant?
OptionA: The electrodes are not connected properly to her basilar membrane.
OptionB: The digital processor has run out of battery so electrical signals are not able to be transmitted to the receiver.
OptionC: The channels along the electrode array are too close together.
OptionD: The electrodes are not sending electrical impulses to the spiral ganglia.
Explanation:
Dr Watson's second hearing lecture explains this. 

 

The electrodes are not normally connected to the basilar membrane, so A is wrong. B and C do not specifically explain why there would be a loss in frequency distinction.

The electrode array takes the place as the basilar membrane; the basilar membrane fibres vibrate at locations specific to the frequency. The electrodes are the same in that specific electrodes along the wire are stimulated at specific frequencies. If the electrodes are too close together, then they will stimulate the same spiral ganglia (or ones that are in very close proximity) and the brain won't be able to distinguish which electrode was stimulated.

Question: What is the physiology behind Kwashiorkor?
OptionA: increase in protein intake, so increased albumin, so osmotic balance is maintained and fluid moves from the blood stream to the tissue, resulting a lower GI tract.
OptionB: decrease in protein intake, so decreased albumin, so osmotic balance is maintained and fluid moves from the tissue to the blood stream, resulting a swollen stomach and abdomen.
OptionC: decrease in protein intake, so decreased albumin, so osmotic balance isn't maintained and fluid moves from the blood stream to the tissue, resulting a swollen stomach and abdomen.
OptionD: decrease in lipid intake, so decreased platelets, so osmotic balance isn't maintained and fluid moves from the blood stream to the tissue, resulting a swollen stomach and abdomen.
OptionE: decrease in vitamin K intake, so decreased albumin, so osmotic balance isn't maintained and fluid moves from the blood stream to the tissue, resulting a swollen stomach.
Explanation:
Correct answer is C 

 

Albumin is a protein and is responsible for maintaining osmotic pressure within the blood stream. 

other functions include: transporting insoluble Fatty acids, steroids and bilirubin. 

 

As there is a decreased intake of protein in the diet, there will be a resulting decrease in albumin, which means the osmotic balance cannot be maintained, so the net movement of fluid is disturbed and fluid will move from the blood stream into the tissues, causing the a swollen stomach and abdomen.

Question: One of the rather 'psychotic' medical student (who tested the conditioning reflex of severed optic chiasm of the dog using red square - RS) has been diagnosed with schizophrenia and has been prescribed with a Dopamine Antagonist. Upon researching on the side effects of this drug, he was very shocked when looking at the very long list. Which of the following option is definitely an adverse effect caused by Dopamine Antagonist?
Explanation:
The main take home message from this question is that Dopamine is an inhibitory pathway for the release of Prolactin from the anterior pituitary gland. 

If Dopamine antagonist is used (usually an anti psychotic drug), this can result in galactorrhoea. Galactorrhea (guh-lack-toe-REE-uh) is a milky nipple discharge unrelated to the normal milk production of breast-feeding. This can happen in both men and women. It happens due to removal of dopamine-mediated inhibition (D2 receptor antagonism) on the lactotrophic cells in the anterior pituitary preventing the release of prolactin.

Question: Which of the following conditions is necessary, in order for a cochlear implant to be a viable option for treatment of hearing loss?
OptionA: There must be no damage to the tympanic membrane.
OptionB: The hearing loss must be conductive, not sensineural.
OptionC: The implant will work only if the hearing loss is mild, not total.
OptionD: The spiral ganglia and cochlear nerve must be intact.
OptionE: The hearing loss must be sensineural, not conductive.
Explanation: Refer to Alan Watson's hearing lectures and the case 6 ear practical sheet. The implant totally bypasses the normal hearing mechanism of the ear, so it does not matter whether hearing loss is conductive or sensineural, up to the level of the cochlea. However, if the spiral ganglia (which are stimulated by the electrodes of the implant) are damaged, or if there is damage to the cochlear division of the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII), which carries auditory impulses to the brain, the implant cannot work.

Question:
Mrs Jones is a 76 year old patient who lives alone. She has recently been brought to A&E after suffering a fall and fracturing her femur. After a moderately long stay in hospital, Mrs Jones has recovered from her injury and is ready to be discharged and is looking forward to returning home. Her son, however, insists she cannot go back to living alone, since he believes she is incapable of living independently. He is very worried that his mother may fall and injure herself again. He also says she has become forgetful recently, and he believes she may have developed dementia.

Mrs Jones' cognitive abilities are assessed via MoCA, and she scores 26/30. She insists she wants to go home, even though she is alone and her family live far away. Her son is adamant she is not capable of making this decision, and points out that it would be unwise for her to go home and risk hurting herself again, since she would have no one around to help her.

 

If the doctors were to listen to Mrs Jones' son, and deem her incapable of making a decision, why would this be a violation of the Mental Capacity Act (2005)?
OptionA: 2nd Principle: Individuals being supported to make their own decisions.
OptionD: No sign of impairment or disturbance to cognitive function - therefore no need for capacity assessment.
OptionE: Mrs Jones has not named her son as LPA (Lasting Power of Attorney).
Explanation:
The Mental Capacity Act is based around 5 core principles:

1) Presumption of Capacity - an individual is to be presumed to have capacity unless it is established otherwise;

2) Individuals being supported to make their own decisions - every step must be taken in order for the individual to understand the circumstances and be able to make the decision (e.g. hearing aid if hearing impairment is present, interpreter if English not first language, etc.)

3) Unwise Decisions - an indivisual is not to be considered incapable simply due to the fact that they make a decision which we judge to be unwise.

4) Best interests - if a decision is made as a consequence of someone being deemed incapable of making their own decision, it must be made in that person's best interests.

5) Less restrictive option - before a decision is made, it must be judged whether or not this decision can be carried out in a way which would interfere less with the person's basic rights and freedoms of action.

 

You may be tempted to answer C - and you are right: it would be wrong to consider Mrs Jones incapable of deciding for herself simply because she is making a decision which seems unwise.

However: her cognitive ability has been tested via the MoCA (Montreal Cognitive Assessment), and she has scored 26. The MoCA scoring guidelines (http://www.bmc.org/Documents/Montreal-cognitive-assessment-MoCA.pdf) consider a score of 26 or higher as normal. Therefore, Mrs Jones has no cognitive impairment, and her capacity to make decisions cannot be disputed by the Mental Capacity Act:

"a person lacks capacity in relation to a matter if at
the material time he is unable to make a decision for himself in relation to the
matter because of an impairment of, or a disturbance in the functioning of, the
mind or brain."

Since she has no impairment or disturbance, by definition, she cannot lack capacity. It is possible that the forgetfulness her son has noticed is simply due to normal ageing, rather than a pathological condition.

Option E would only become relevant in the scenario in which Mrs Jones had been deemed incapable, and a person would have to make a decision in her stead.

Question:
A patient presents with symptoms of jaundice and you decide to carry out some tests to determine the source of the problem.

 

Plasma unconjugated bilirubin is HIGH

Plasma and urine conjugated bilirubin are NORMAL

Reticulocytes are HIGH

Haemoglobin is LOW

All other liver function tests are normal

 

What type of jaundice is this?
Explanation:
Prehepatic unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia is caused by excess haemolysis, defects of red blood cell metabolism or defects in haemoglobin production.

i.e. Liver function is normal

 

In this case;

Plasma unconjugated bilirubin is raised because excess unconjugated bilirubin is produced and there is too much for the liver to conjugate.

Plasma and urine conjugated bilirubin are normal because the liver is functioning at its normal rate and conjugating a normal amount of bilirubin.

Reticulocytes are immature red blood cells. Therefore there will be more of them due to excess breakdown of haemoglobin/RBCs

Haemoglobin is low because it is being abnormally broken down.

All other liver function tests are normal because the liver is functioning normally.

Question: Which of the following muscles would be most vulnerable to a strain?

Hence, they are said to be biarticulate. Biarticulate muscles are more vulnerable to strain because they have to stretch further.
