Question:
Mr Jones is a 42 year old man who has come into your clinic presenting with pain at the back of the foot especially near the heel. He tells you that the pain began when he changed direction quickly during a squash match. He also described a "sudden popping" feeling when it occurred. 

 

You expect Mr Jones to have ruptured his Archilles tendon so you carry out a Simmonds-Thompson test. Which of the following is incorrect, with regards to results of the Simmonds-Thompson test?
OptionA: In a positive test there would be no movement of the foot when you squeeze the gastrocnemius.
OptionB: In a negative test there would be plantarflexion of the foot (toes point down) when you squeeze the gastrocnemius
OptionC: In a negative test there would be no movement of the foot when you squeeze the gastrocnemius.
OptionD: Plantar flexion of the foot when you squeeze the gastrocnemius is normal so if present would indicate no Archilles rupture.
OptionE: No movement of the foot when you squeeze the gastrocnemius is abnormal so is indicative of an Archilles rupture.
Explanation:
A negative test means there is no Archilles rupture (not no movement) 

 

Positive test: no movement when you squeeze the gastrocnemius which suggests the Archilles has been ruptured.

Negative test: plantarflexion when you squeeze the gastrocnemius which suggests the Archilles hasn't been ruptured.

 

Spontaneous tendon rupture is most common during sporting activities - especially in eccentric contraction. They are also most common in 40-45 year olds.

 

Pain and "sudden popping" are both characteristics of a tendon rupture.

Question: What is inhibins main role in the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle?
Explanation: Inhibin is released by the corpus luteum after ovulation along with oestrogen and progesterone. Inhibin inhibits FSH in order to stop a new primary follicle maturing into a secondary follicle. Progesterone inhibits GnRH which means that LH decreases (GnRH causes the anterior pituitary to release LH and FSH). Progesterone, Inhibin and oestrogen all decrease after day 21 (because teh corpus luteum degenerates) which means that GnRH increases starting the new menstrual cycle. Progesterone also maintains the endometrium so after the levels decrease the lining is shed.

Question: Where is CSF produced in the brain?

Question: Which of these brain cells has a protective function?
Explanation:
Oligodendrocytes main function is myelination.

Microglia are the cells with a protective role- they are activated by brain injury and protect neurons from pathogens. They also carry out phagocytosis.

Astrocytes have many functions including: ensuring syncitium (where all cells are physically connected to each other in some way), being present in the blood-brain barrier and ensuring certain ion concentrations don't get too high (e.g. potassium).

Neurons are the main brain cells and transmit information 

Ependymal cells are ciliated cuboidal epithelial cells in ventricles which contribute to some CSF production.

Question: A critically ill patient comes into A&E requiring antibiotic treatment. Which method of administration would be most suitable for this patient?
Explanation:
• Oral administration takes 1-2 hours for the antibiotic to reach maximal plasma concentration and if the patient is critically ill this is not quick enough. In addition if the drug is not resistant to acid then it make not reach the site of infection (e.g. lower GI tract) because it will be broken down in the stomach and released too early. This means a lower than therapeutic level reaches the site of infection.
  • IM injections take 0.5-1 hour to reach maximal plasma concentration.
  • IV infusions take 20-30 minutes to reach maximal plasma concentration, therefore the best and quickest way to treat critically ill patients with antibiotics.
  • Topical - antibiotics can be incorporated into creams. Although useful in infections of the extremities in people with poor circulation (e.g. diabetics) who can't get the antibiotic to peripheral regions, it probably won't be useful for a critically ill patient.
  • Intrathecal injection - this involves injecting the antibiotic into the spinal canal. It is not used because it can cause fits.

Question: What is the treatment for paracetamol overdose?
Explanation:
Usually in the liver, the majority of paracetamol is glucuronidated and sulfated. A small amount forms NAPQI which is toxic to hepatocytes. The NAPQI is dealt with by conjugating it with glutathione. In a paracetamol overdose the sulfination/glucuronidation pathways are saturated so a large amount of paracetamol forms NAPQI, this means that the glutathione reserves are used up and the NAPQI remains toxic and at high levels which leads to damage to the liver. 

N-acetylcysteine is a precursor to glutathione so will increase glutathione levels and will cause the conjugation of NAPQI, resulting in a decrease in toxicity.

Question: What is the cut off point (in hours) when inflammation goes from acute to chronic?
Explanation:
Polymorphic neutrophils (PMNs) have a lifespan of around 2 days. After this time they have finished their tasks and die by apoptosis. The macrophages will then come and phagocytose the cell debris this leaves.

At 48-96 hours macrophages replace PMNs are the primary cell type in damaged/infected tissue.

It is at this point the inflammation can be described as having changed from acute to chronic. 

 

Source: Case 1 Cutaneous Wound Healing Lecture.

Question: Gluconeogenesis is an important process when in the fasted state. Which is the rate limiting step....
Explanation:
A) G-6-Phosphotase is an important enzyme in that it converts G6P into Glucose. This is important because when Glucose is in its phosphorylated state (G6P) it is essentially 'trapped' inside the cell. Therefore since Glycogen is converted into G6P before being converted into Glucose, then the availability of G-6-phosphatase determines whether Glucose can be released into circulation....

  • Muscle cells lack G-6-phosphotase = they do not 'share' their glycogen stores because Glycogen can only be converted as far as G6P and cannot be dephosphorylated in order to be released from the cell. Therefore the G6P simply continues down the glycolysis pathway
  • Liver cells have plenty of G-6-phosphotase = therefore is able to 'share' glycogen reserves with the rest of the body because G6P can be dephosphorylatedf

B) made up

 

C) CORRECT; (it is inhibited by Fructose-2,6-bisphosphat)

Link to fasting >>>Glucagon, through PKA, activates the FBPase2 (D) domain of the bifunctional enzyme (PFK2/FBPase2) which converts Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate back into Fructose-6-phospate. The removal of F26BP means less inhibition of gluconeogenesis therefore more glucose is made.

Question: The respiratory exchange ratio (RER) is the ratio between the amount of carbon dioxide (CO2) produced in metabolism and oxygen (O2) used. You measure the RER of a patient and get a value of 0.7. What can you conclude that the primary fuel source being used is in this case?
Explanation:
RER of 0.70 indicates that fat is the predominant fuel source

RER of 1.00 or above  is indicative of carbohydrate being the predominant fuel source.

RER between 0.7-1.00 suggests a mix of fat and carbohydrates

 


The reason as to why using fats leads to a lower respiratory quotient is that less CO2 is released. This is because the link reaction is missed out, where CO2 is usually a by-product. therefore since the eqn is Volume of CO2/Volume of O2 a smaller number on top will lead to a smaller RQ.

Question: A 76 year old female with a known history of smoking presents at her GP. She complains of having a droopy right eyelid (ptosis) and on inspection you find her right pupil is constricted (miosis). It is later discovered that she has a tumour which is causing these symptoms. Where is the tumour most likely present?
Explanation:
Ptosis and miosis present together is known as Horner's syndrome. It is the result of damage or compression of the superior cervical ganglion of the sympathetic trunk. Therefore loss of sympathetic innervation to the levator palpabrae (causing droopy eye/ptosis) and radial muscles of iris (causing pupillary constriction/miosis).

 

Most likely cause of compression to sympathetic trunk is a tumour in the apex of lung = Pancoast tumour. 

 

Resources- Question in PCS 3 anatomy (green) books, "communication and control" and Dr Watson "orbit, eye and vision" PCS 3 lecture.

Question: Which of the following definitions best describes secondary hyperalgesia?
OptionA: Prolonged activation of nociceptive fibres leads to accumulation of substance P in the dorsal horn. This leads to a wind-up in activity of the nociceptive pathway. There is increased responsiveness to NMDA glutamate receptors which potentiates the response at glutamatergic NMDA-dependent nociceptive synapses leading to increases pain sensitivity.
OptionB:
Substance P stimulates the release of histamine and serotonin from mast cells. Prostaglandins (formed from the breakdown products of the cell membrane at the site of injury) and bradykinin (formed from the breakdown products of the extracellular molecules at the site of injury) are also formes.

Together this substances increase the sensitivity of the nociceptive sensory endings leading to increased pain sensitivity.
OptionC: Touch sensitive sensory neurones (low threshold mechanoreceptors) start to generate the sensation of pain.
Explanation:
A = secondary hyperalgesia

B = primary algesia

C = allodynia

Question:

Question: Where would you find the soleal line?
OptionB: The line formed by the joining of the pectineal line and gluteal tuberosity
OptionD: Goes on to form the floor of the popliteal fossa
OptionE: Between the greater and lesser trochanters of the femur
Explanation:
The soleal line is a ridge of bone that marks the posterior surface of the tibia.

 

It is the intertrochanteric line that runs between the greater and lesser trochanters of the femur.

Once the intertrochanteric crest has passed below the lesser trochanter, it forms the pectineal line, which joins with the gluteal tuberosity (from the greater trochanter) to form the linea aspera (Runs down the shaft of the posterior femur)

The linea aspera splits into the medial and lateral supracondylar lines at the distal femur and goes on to form the floor of the popliteal fossa.

Question: What does a positive Trendelenburg sign suggest the damage of?
Explanation:
The superior gluteal nerve innervates the gluteus medius and minimus muscles.

In the standing position, these muscles contract when the contralateral leg is raised (Preventing the pelvis from dropping towards the raised leg). If the nerve supply to these muscles is damaged, then the muscles are paralysed and unable to contract. This leads to a pelvic drop of the unsupported leg.

Question:
A 16 year-old patient visits your clinic complaining of a sore throat, muscle weakness and loss of appetite. Following examination you notice that the patient is also pyrexic and has enlarged lymph nodes. The young man is a keen rugby player, and he tells you that his team always share bottles to drink water during matches. You suspect infection with Epstein-Barr virus, which is common in teenagers and young adults, and can be transmitted via saliva. You order serologic tests to confirm the diagnosis.

 

Which immunoglobulin class is generally the first to be generated in response to infection, and therefore allows you to determine whether infection is acute or chronic via serology?
Explanation:
IgM is the correct answer, since IgM is the first type of antibody produced by B cells in response to infection. IgM circulates as a pentamer, and therefore is very good at activating the complement system (via the classical pathway).

 

However, the size of the pentamer leads to IgM having bad tissue penetration, which means that following the initial response, B cells switch to secretion of IgG (smaller, monomeric, more diverse effector functions). IgG is also the only antibody which can cross the placenta, and therefore will be the class of antibody present in a baby's serum.

 

IgA is useful in the defence of mucosal tissues, such as those present in the lungs, GI tract and urogenital tracts, thanks to its dimeric form which allows it to cross these mucosal layers. It is the secretory antibody found in breast milk, and, therefore, will be the type of antibody which you can find in a baby's gut. It is not, however, the first class of antibody produced.

 

IgE has a role in the activation of mast cells in response to a parasitic infection, but, again, it is not the first type to be produced.

 

I constructed this question and the explanation from my notes on immunology from the revision session during consolidation week.

 

The functions of IgD are largely still under debate, and for the scope of our course we are not required to explore them for now :)

Question: Which type of muscle contraction controls joint movement?
Explanation:
Isotonic contraction- tension occurs in the muscles while there is a change in muscle length. There are 2 types:

  • concentric- causes joint movement (tension develops as muscle shortens)
  • eccentric-controls movement (tension develops as muscle lengthens

Isometric contraction stops joint movement (tension develops in muscle but there is no change in muscle length)

Question: Leiomyoma is the formation of fibroid tissue in the uterus. It is differentiated according to its location in the uterine wall. A subserosal leiomyoma would be found:

Question: HCN channels are important in what phase of a cardiac pacemaker action potential?
Explanation:
The order of phases for a pacemaker action potential is... 4 > 0 > 3

  • Phase 4/funny current = Na+ leaks in through HCN channels causing slow depolarisation. Once threshold is reached, triggers phase 0
  • Phase 0 = voltage gated Ca2+ channels open leading to  calcium influx and hence accelerated depolarisation. 
  • Phase 3 = voltage gated K+ channels open leading to K+ efflux and therefore repolarisation occurs 

 

NB phase 1 and 2 only found in cardiac myocyte AP

Question: In a cardiac myocyte action potential which phase does the plateau occur and which ion is responsible?
Explanation:
Cardiac myocyte action potential has 5 phases...

  • Phase 4 = is the resting phase. Happens due to slow efflux of K+ which maintains the resting potential at a negative value
  • Phase 0 = when neighbouring cells depolarise it causes Na+ voltage gated channels to open very quickly, theerfore Na+ floods in causing the very steep depolarisation 
  • Phase 1 = voltage gated K+ channels open > K+ efflux > starting to repolarise
  • Phase 2 = repolarisation is interrupted by opening of v.g Ca2+ channels. Ca2+ influx opposes K+ efflux hence the plateau 
  • Phase 3 = v.g Ca2+ channels shut and therefore K+ efflux continues unopposed therefore repolarisation back to resting potential

Question: What is the condition gigantism primarily attributed to?
Explanation:
It is primarily high levels of IGF-1 during development when the epiphyseal growth plates are still open that are attributed to gigantism. This leads to a proportional increase in size (bones and soft tissue both affected).

Generally speaking, somatostatin inhibits growth hormone releasing hormone (GHRH). It is growth hormone inhibiting hormone (GHIH) that induces the effects of somatostatin. High cortisol levels also inhibit growth. However, it is high IGF-1 that is primarily associated with gigantism. IGF is secreted by the liver and involved in skeletal and soft tissue growth.

Question: Leukocyte extravasation is a multi-step process which is important in inflammation. Which of the following is important in the firm adhesion of leukocytes to the endothelial wall of blood vessels?
Explanation:
Correct answer is D 

 

Inflammation can be split into 2 main events >> > VASCULAR & CELLULAR

 

Vascular events include the dilation of blood vessels and ^ in permeability.

- vasodilation mainly mediated by histamine and NO > increase blood flow explains the redness and heat seen in inflammation. vasodilation also = vascular stasis; which is important for margination of leukocytes

-^ vascular permeability is mediated again by substances like Histamine, NO and also TNFalpha. 

 

Cellular events

ie leukocyte extravasation

  1. Margination - blood cells move to periphery
  2. Rolling - cytokines such as IL1 and TNFalpha cause endothelial cells to express selectins (E/P) = neutrophils slow down and 'roll' 
  3. Firm adhesion - chemokines cause neutrophils to express integrins = allows firm fixation to endothelium
  4. Transmigration - PCAMs

Question:
A 65 yr old female patient comes into clinic complaining of chest tightness and nausea when exercising, but this subsides post exercise.

Junior doctor on call prescribes glyceryl trinitrate, what does this do after it is reduced in the body.
Explanation: drugs like isosorbide mononitrate and glyceryl trinitrate are reduced in the body to nitrogen oxide. this activates guanyl cyclase in vascular smooth muscle. cGMP activates protein kinase G which prevents calcium entry into smooth muscle cells. this causes smooth muscle cells to dilate and hence reduces issues such as ischaemia.

Question: Pt. comes in to clinic, post examination it is found her angina is deteriorating rapidly. The doctor prescribes Beta Blockers and then asks you to explain to the patient briefly their function, what do you include in your explanation.
Explanation: beta blockers are inhibitors of beta 1 adrenoreceptor, this prevents the binding of adrenaline and noradrenaline therefore reducing heart rate and heart force, which reduces myocardial oxygen demand.

Question: Which of the following forms a key part of the pain inhibition system?
Explanation:
A) part of the ascending pain pathway = noxious stimuli is transduced and transmitted along pain fibres (A delta, C) to the substantia gelatinosa of the dorsal horn >>ascends in the contralateral spinothalamic tract to the brain for cortical processing (either medial or lateral pain system)

B) C) Medial pain system = Medial thalamic nuclei, ACC and insula

D) Lateral pain system = lateral thalamic nuclei and primary/secondary somatosensory cortices

E) CORRECT PAG is part of the pain inhibition system (Descending pain modulatory system)

 

Psych. of Pain lecture: Dr Thannasi Hassoulas

Question: A 70 yr old patient comes in to the walk in clinic at the GP, the patient is a retired doctor himself so asks for a vasodilator to reduce his ischaemia, the GP agrees but says he has the perfect drug to solve his ischaemia with the primary impact of vasodilation in mind. Which drug is he most likely to mention?
Explanation:
CCBs like verapamil cause vasodilation by preventing vascular smooth muscle cell contraction plus they reduce the force of ventricle contraction and rate limit the heart (reducing cardiac output) and thus best option for ischamia as almost a double effect.

 

Nicorandil is the only other drug on the list that causes vasodilation but obviously double effect of CCB outweights simple vasodilation. SBAs means best suited answer.

Question: Which ligaments create the divide between the greater and lesser sciatic foramina?
Explanation:
The sacrospinous ligament traverses the sciatic foramen from the sacrum to the spine of the ischium.

It is interwoven with fibres from the sacrotuberous ligament, which originates at the sacrum (posteriorly) and attaches at the ischial tuberosity (posteriorly).

 

The greater sciatic foramen is further divided by the piriformis muscle, below which the sciatic nerve emerges

Question: Noradrenaline acts on which receptor the most to increase blood pressure?
Explanation:
noradrenaline activates alpha 1 receptors to cause vasoconstriction and increase blood pressure - sympathetic.

 

adrenaline activates beta 2 receptors to cause vasodilation and decrease blood pressure - sympathetic

 

Parasympathetic activity causes vasodilation - can be ACh, bradykinin or kallikreins

Question: A consultant is having a stroll around the wards picking on junior doctors and asking them questions, one of the questions he asks is,"which biomarker would one look for that indicates cardiac damage?"
Explanation:
We used to use creatine kinase because it shows when there has been cardiac myocyte damage but it also comes up in skeletal muscle damage and thus is not specific so now we look at troponin. this is done by an immunoassay which is a test using antibodies/immunoglobulins to detect something.
Although one form of CK is specific to cardiac damage- CK-MB.

Question: Doctor prescribes aspirin. What does this do?
Explanation: Aspirin is a thromboxane A2 inhibitor, by inhibiting TXA2 it stops formation of GPIIb/IIIa which is the final step in common pathway required to form a clot.

Question: A doctor is having a review of patient medications after clinic, he decides to prescribe clopidogrel along with the already prescribed aspirin for one of his patients. What is the MOA of clopidogrel?
Explanation:
Clopidogrel works synergistically with aspirin to prevent clots. V useful.

 

Hope this helps.

Question:
Your 50 year old self is woken in the night by a spot of central crushing chest pain, you're a medic so you decide to do your own ECG, you find that you have quite a tall T wave and ST segment elevation in leads II, III and aVF as well as ST depression in aVL
Which of the following is most likely to be causing your discomfort?
Explanation:
the ST elevation in the inferior leads with reciprocal ST depression in aVL is indicitive of an inferior STEMI

 

II, III, aVF are inferior leads (suggesting Right Coronary Artery is affected)
V1, V2, V3, V4 are anterior leads (suggesting Left Anterior Descending artery is affected)
V5, V6 are lateral leads (Suggest Left Circumflex is affected, lead I and aVL usually also abnormal)
 
an NSTEMI would have ST depression indicating myocardial ischaemia (not elevation)

A - anterior leads would be affected and ST elevation would not be seen
B - anterior leads would be affected
C - ST elevation would not be seen
D - Correct
E - wouldn't have the abnormal ECG but could be causing the pain.

also waking up in the middle of the night with pain/indigestion is a common presentation of MI.

T x

Question: . There are two types of MHC proteins, both of which are important for T-cell activation. These are classified ed into Class I and Class II. Which single cell type does not display MHC type I proteins on its surface?
Explanation: A s the MHC class I proteins are displayed on nearly all nucleated cells in the body, the correct answer is the non-nucleated erythrocyte. Exceptions to the rule include nucleated syncytiotrophoblast cells in the placenta and neurones which lack MHC class I molecules. The class I MHC proteins are recognized by cytotoxic CD8 T-cells. The role of the class I MHC proteins is vital as they signal to cytotoxic T-cells that infectious microorganisms are hidden with the cells of the body. The class I protein is made within the cell and then binds to an 8–9 amino acid peptide produced by the cell which is either ‘self’ or ‘foreign’. The loaded class I MHC protein is then transported to the plasma membrane. In this way, virally infected and cancerous cells are recognized. The class II MHC proteins are expressed on antigen-presenting cells.

Question:
John, a 35 year-old male, comes into the clinic with symptoms of generalised muscle pain and early fatigue when he tries to walk at a fast pace with his dogs. After examination and testing, he is diagnosed with McArdle's disease.

 

Which enzyme is deficient in McArdle's disease?
Explanation:
McArdle's disease is also known as Glycogen Storage Disease Type V

 

Glycogen storage diseases can be due to either glycogen synthesis or breakdown

 

In McArdle's disease, it is a deficiency in Myophosphorylase (the muscle isoform of glycogen phosphorylase)

 

 

If you look at the above diagram, if you are deficient in phosphorylase, the body cannot efficiently use glycogen as an energy source during exercise. However if you slowly build up your exercise and hit a 'second wind', when fatty acids are used as an energy source, then patients with the disease will experience less pain and fatigue.

 

You can see the roles of B and C in glycogenolysis.

A - Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase - the rate-limiting step of gluconeogenesis

E - Phosphofructokinase - the Rate-limiting step of glycolysis

 

This disease came up in 'Adaptations to Exercise' small group, in PCS Unit 1
Tags: Andrew Shore, Metabolism, Biochemistry, PCS Unit 1

Question:
You're a senior consultant. You've made it this far.

Its another busy night in A&E and somehow you've been roped in to do another 12 hour shift (short staffing or something).

A young woman comes in with fever, diarrhoea, jaundice and upper right quadrant abdominal pain.
One of those switched on junior doctors has run some tests and found the following:

HBsAg = Neg.
anti-HBc= Neg.
anti-HBs= Pos.
IgM = Neg.
IgG= Neg.

However, that same junior doctor's gran had Hepatitis D, so he is now convinced that this patient has the same, as she is 'presenting with similar symptoms'.
Which of the following is the most indicative that he is unfortunately wrong?
OptionE: He's run tests for Hepatitis B.... That proves nothing!
Explanation:
First of all, FairPlay to the junior doctor running tests.

The answer is B because....

A- IgM indicates acute infection, yes this would be relevant if he has acute Hep.D, but its not too relevant here.
B- The fact that the patient has tested positive for anti-Hbs and negative for anti-HBc tells us she's been vaccinated. Hepatitis D can't live without its best friend B, so if she's immune from Hep.B she's also immune from Hep.D! This means the junior doctor is wrong.

C- This tells us she hasn't had hepatitis B, so therefore can't have hepatitis D.
D-This would be true for acute Hepatitis B and D, but is also elevated in other pathologies.
E- This would have been a good call if he had had hepatitis.

The woman could possibly have Hepatitis C, but thats for another question.
Tags: Liver, Case 4, Hand anatomy, PCS unit 2, Immunology

Question:
A 62 year old male patient comes into your clinic presenting with gynaecamastia (enlargement of the breast tissue).

You look at his records and you see that in the past he has come in because he has suffered from "heartburn". 

What medication may this patient be on that is cause his gynaecamastia?
Explanation:
H2RAs cause gynaecomastia in male patients because they act as an anti-androgen.

 

Another important undesired effect H2RAs have is that they inhibit the CYP enzymes. These are the enzymes that carry out phase I metabolism of drugs in the liver. Drugs such as warfarin are metabolised by this enzyme, so the H2RAs stop the metabolism of these drugs > drugs accumulate > toxic effects. 

 

Case 3: Therapeutics of the Upper GI Tract Lecture

Question: A patient with a bleeding disorder has a normal prothrombin time (PT) and normal bleeding time? Which of the following bleeding disorders is it most likely to be?
Explanation:
CORRECT ANSWER IS HAEMOPHILIA

 

Diagnosis of Haemophilia

 

Normal...

  • Prothrombin time (PT) - this is a test for the extrinsic pathway which Factor VIII/IX are not a part of therefore is unaffected
  • Bleeding time - is also normal. This may sound confusing but bleeding time is a test for platelet function, which is unaffected in Haemophilia due to it being a disease of coagulation factors THERFORE clotting time time is prolonged not bleeding time ----NB/ in von Willebrand disease and thrombocytopaenia, platelets are affected therefore bleeding time WILL be prolonged hence why answer is not B/C)

Prolonged...

  • Activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT) - test for intrinsic pathway which factors VIII/IX are a part of therefore will be affected
  • Clotting time - haemophillia affects intrinsic pathway of CLOTTING cascade therefore CLOTTING time is also affected

Question:
It is the final minute of the last match in a five-a-side tournament with your friends on Taly 3G. The opposing team has the ball and if they score they will win and have bragging rights for the rest of the year. Their best player is running past you and is about to shoot but you cannot allow that to happen: you slide in for the hardest tackle Talybont sports facilities have ever seen and your mate crashes down to the floor, clutching his ankle and screaming with pain. You remember learning about the Ottawa Ankle Rules at a radiology tutorial during Case 1, and decide to try your hand at applying them to your friend's ankle. After a careful examination you tell your mate he should man up and that your tackle was "100% ball". After a few minutes he's walking fine and has no problem putting weight on the "injured" ankle as you make your way to Taly Social for a couple of well deserved post-match pints.

 

What are the Ottawa Ankle Rules, and what do they allow you to determine?
OptionA: A set of rules which allow you to determine the exact site at which a patient has fractured their ankle.
OptionB: A set of rules which allow you to determine specific points to massage on a patient's ankle to temporarily relieve pain.
OptionC: A set of rules which allow you to determine whether or not an acute ankle injury requires surgical intervention.
OptionD: A set of rules which allow you to determine whether or not a patient is faking acute pain.
OptionE: A set of rules which allow you to determine whether or not a patient requires an ankle X-Ray following acute ankle injury.
Explanation:
I don't know how important this may be for exams, but it came up in one of our radiology tutorials and I reckon it is interesting for anyone who does sport or is interested in that aspect of Medicine. The Ottawa Ankle Rules are a set of guidelines, which includes areas of the foot/ankle to palpate, and observation of the patient's ability to bear weight. The examination and these rules allow you to determine whether or not a patient requires an X-ray following an acute ankle injury. They were created because previously radiographs were ordered for anyone presenting with this type of injury, leading to a large waste of resources.

Question: What is the mechanism of action of Beta-Adrenergic Agonists such as Salbumatol (Short-term use for asthma)?
OptionA: Increases cGMP from activation of guanylyl cyclase which leads to bronchodilation
OptionB: Decreases cGMP from activation of guanylyl cyclase which leads to bronchoconstriction
OptionC: Increases cAMP from activation of adenylyl cyclase which leads to bronchoconstriction
OptionD: Decreases cAMP from activation of adenylyl cyclase which leads to bronchodilation
OptionE: Increases cAMP from activation of adenylyl cyclase which leads to bronchodilation
Explanation: Beta-Adrenergic Agonists activate adenylyl cyclase which leads to cAMP production. cAMP is a secondary messenger and at the end of the cascade, it leads to dilation of smooth muscle.

Question: What sensory receptor detects changes in PCO2 or H+ concentration at the carotid sinuses?
Explanation:
Chemoreceptors detect changes in blood gas composition, specifically for an increase in PCO2 or proton concentration.

 

Baroreceptors detect blood pressure changes

Stretch receptors are mechanoreceptors to help prevent overinflation

Irritant receptors are in the nose and alveoli to help prevent lung damage

Proprioceptors are in the Golgi Tendon Organs in the ribcage muscles

Question: Elidh presents at a GPs office with a chest infection. Which of these innate defences is an anatomical barrier to infection?
Explanation: The most correct answer is the mucous membranes in the respiratory system. All the others listed are physiological barriers.

Question:
Josie has sustained a deep gash in her right thigh. Fortunately, you have been trained in first aid and manage to treat and dress the wound adequately.
You and Josie begin discussing lymphatics. Which of these would be the final lymphatic structure that the lymphocytes from her right thigh would eventually drain into?
Explanation: The most correct answer is the thoracic duct. The thoracic duct drains everything inferior to the diaphragm and left side of upper body. The right thoracic duct drains lymph from right side of upper body superior to the diaphragm. Although the lymphocytes may pass through the cisterna chyli and the inguinal lymph nodes, they are not the final lymphatic structure as the question asks for
Tags: Anatomy, PCS unit 2, Immunology, Lymphatic System

Question: IgG is an antibody which is transferred from mother to child via the placenta. What type of cells produce and secrete IgG?
Explanation:
The most correct answer is plasma cells because B cells differentiate into plasma cells which then synthesize and secrete antibodies. B cells are technically correct but plasma cell is a more specific answer.
Helper T cells stimulate activation and function of B and T cells.
Memory T cells respond to previously encountered pathogens.
Leukocytes aren’t specific because lymphocytes are types of leukocytes and B and T cells are examples of lymphocytes.
Tags: Endocrinology, Reproductive Physiology, PCS unit 2, Hormone, Immunology

Question: Judith, a keen 16 year old who is fascinated by immunology asks her mum an immunologist the following question. If the thymus failed to produce thymic hormones, which immune cells’ production would it affect.
Explanation: The most correct answer is T lymphocyte because T cells mature in the thymus. They undergo differentiation here to become mature so any problem with the thymus would affect this process. Plasma cells are fully differentiated B lymphocytes, which mature in the red bone marrow. Lymphocytes aren’t specific enough and could include either B or T cells. Natural killer cells mature in the red bone marrow.

Question: Mrs Jones is the mother of 18 month old Aimee. She is currently pregnant with another child. Aimee has just woken up from sleep and is being breastfed by Mrs Jones. Which hormone is responsible for stimulating the synthesis of milk by the mammary gland and which antibody is released to Aimee in the process of breastfeeding?
Explanation:
The most correct answer is Prolactin and IgA. Prolactin stimulates the synthesis of milk by the mammary glands whilst oxytocin is responsible for the let-down of milk.
IgA is released via breast milk and IgG is released via placenta
Tags: Endocrinology, Reproductive Physiology, PCS Unit 3, PCS unit 2, Immunology

Question: Mrs Jones is breastfeeding Aimee. She starts reflecting on her doctor’s appointment when she was told that her 4 month old unborn baby would be receiving immune protection from an antibody she synthesises. Which hormone is responsible for the let-down of milk and which antibody will Mrs Jones’ unborn baby be receiving from her?
Explanation:
The most correct answer is oxytocin and IgG. Prolactin stimulates the synthesis of milk by the mammary glands whilst oxytocin is responsible for the let down of milk.
IgA is released via breast milk and IgG is released via placenta. Vasopressin is anti-diuretic hormone (ADH) which increases the permeability of the collecting duct and part of the distal convoluted tubule to water in the kidneys.

Question: 10 year old Tom presents with an acute viral infection. What would you expect to be elevated in regards to non-specific immunity?
Explanation: The most correct answer is Interferons. T cells and plasma cells are associated with specific/acquired immunity, not non-specific/innate immunity as the question asks for. Although there may be raised levels of macrophages and complement proteins with viral infections, interferons are very important. Their levels rise during viral infections and they produce antivirals which interfere with viral replication inside the cell.

Question: You and your best friend are discussing the differentiation of leukocytes. She asks what types of cells in the liver would e affected by a decrease in the number of monocyte forming cells in red bone marrow. Which of these is the best suited answer.
Explanation:
The most correct answer is Kupffer cells. Monocytes differentiate into macrophages however this question specifically asks about the liver. Remember that macrophages can be given specific names depending on where they are found. Kupffer cells are macrophages of the liver, microglial cells are macrophages of the brain. Plasma cells are fully differentiated B cells ad although they mature in the red bone marrow they come from lymphoid stem cells not monocytes.
T lymphocytes mature in the thymus and come from lymphoid stem cells
Tags: Case 3, PCS unit 2, Immunology, Cell Differentiation

Question: Gregory presents with a decrease in the number of B cells. Which type of immunity would be most affected by this
Explanation:
The most correct answer is humoral immunity – this is mediated by B cells.
Innate and non-specific immunity mean the same thing. They are mediated by phagocytes, complement system, interferons, inflammation, fever and natural killer cells. Acquired immunity refers to B and T cells, however this isn’t specific enough for the question. Cell mediated immunity is due to T cells.

Question: An aspect of innate immunity is the activation of the complement system. During a lesson you are discussing the complement system and how one of its outcomes can lead to the formation of the membrane attack complex (MAC) on a pathogen which can lead to cell death. What type of cell death does the pathogen undergo
Explanation:
The most correct answer is necrosis. This involves cellular lysis and the release of intracellular components. Apoptosis and programmed cell death refer to the same thing- this involves shrinkage of the cell, condensation of chromatin, cell blebbing and ends with phagocytosis of the cell fragments
Atrophy refers to wasting of an organ, muscle or tissue
Cytokinesis refers to the formation of a cleavage furrow at the end of mitosis

Question: A budding young medical-student-to-be saunters along to his GP to receive the mandatory Hepatitis B vaccination he requires before being released into the dangerous world of needle-sticks, infected patients, and the odd drunken, risqué night out. After the course of three immunisations, he goes along for a blood test to check his status. What should the results show?
OptionA:
HBsAg negative

Anti-HBc positive

Anti-HBs positive

IgM-anti HBc negative

IgG-anti HBc negative
OptionB:
HBsAg negative

Anti-HBc negative

Anti-HBs positive

IgM-anti HBc negative

IgG-anti HBc negative
OptionC:
HBsAg positive

Anti-HBc positive

Anti-HBs negative

IgM-anti HBc positive

IgG-anti HBc negative
OptionD:
HBsAg positive

Anti-HBc positive 

Anti-HBs negative

HBsAg- negative

Anti-HBc- positive

Question: Mannose & Fucose are carbohydrates found on the cell wall of bacteria. What aspect of the complement system do they activate?
Explanation:
There are 3 pathways that lead to complement activation.

  • Classical. Basically as a result of IgG or IgM antibodies bound to a pathogen.
  • Lectin. This is the correct answer. Mannose binding lectin (MBL) is a protein that binds to the carbohydrates found on bacteria cell walls (mannose/fucose), and when it does so it activates this pathway of the complement. This carbohydrates are not found on human cells.
  • Alternative. This pathway is activated by the spontaneous production of low levels of C3a and C3b, which is accelerated on invading bacterial or fungal cells. 

Simply all pathways lead to production of complement C3 which then forms C3a and C3b. It is C3b that then goes on to to bind with C5 and form the membrane attack complex. 

 


Complement freaked me out a bit at the start which is why I made this question! I found p346 of Pocock helpful at breaking it down!

If any of my info is wrong or I could explain something better please leave a comment :)

Question:
On his way to pick up his latest hot date, Luca starts to wonder how the petrol in his car makes it move, his train of thought leads him to think about his body using ATP as an energy source.
Which definition best describes ATP coupling?
OptionA: Using 2 molecules of ATP rather than one in order to speed up the rate of a metabolic reaction.
OptionB: Using the reaction of ATP alongside a reaction that requires energy, in order to supply the energy and make that reaction happen spontaneously.
OptionC: Reacting ATP with something else, in order to transfer ATP's energy to the reaction, thus causing an endothermic reaction.
OptionD: The reaction between ADP and Pi to make a molecule of ATP using adenylyl cyclase.
OptionE: The production of 2 ATP molecules in Glycolysis.
Explanation:
In a coupled reaction energy required by 1 process is supplied by another process by coupling the 2 reactions. (This makes the overall reaction spontaneous and is independent of whether the reaction is endo/exothermic).

Question:
To celebrate the end of their exams the lads are heading out for the cheekiest of nandos. Jack plans to devour a whole chicken. As a regular Jack is aware that this chicken will contain approximately 7.6g of carbohydrate, plus 1.9g from the extra hot spice baste that he'll get to show the lads how alpha he is.
Assuming that all of the carbohydrate is converted to glucose, what will the glucose concentration in mmol/L of jack's stomach contents be once he has completed his feast?

 

Normal volume of liquid in jack's stomach: 100ml

Mr glucose: 180 g/mol
Explanation:
A - add the 2 carbohydrate masses together at the beginning & you have not converted mols to mmols

B - remember to convert mols to mmols

C - make sure you add the 2 carbohydrate masses together at the beginning

D - :)

E - rounding error


CORRECT WORKING:


Total Carbohydrate ingested: 7.6+1.9 = 9.5g 

 

Mols=Mass/Mr

Mols of glucose= 9.5/180 = 0.0528 mols (actually 0.052777r so round up to 528)


Concentration=mols/volume
100ml = 0.1L
Concentration of glucose = 0.0527/0.1 = 0.528 mols/L

(x103 = 527.7777778 mmol/L)

 

note 1L also = 1 dm3

Question: A patient on a respiratory ward has had a pulmonary embolism in his left lung. In the area of physiological dead space what would you expect to happen to the partial pressures of 02 and CO2 ?

As there is a blockage of blood supply to the ventilated alveoli (physiological dead space) no carbon dioxide will exit the blood into the alveoli so partial pressure will be 0. Inhaled oxygen will not be able to pass from the alveoli into the blood and so it's partial pressure will increase.

Question: Gemeprost is usually used in conjunction with Mifepristone as an abortifacient. It is an analogue of...
Explanation:
Gemeprost is an abortifacient usually administered with Mifepristone.

 

Why together? Mifepristone is a progesterone receptor antagonist and plays 2 roles.

Firstly, since it is an antagonist then it prevents progesterone from doing its normal job i.e maintaining  the endometrium/a viable environment for the foetus. Therefore if it is prevented from doing this then >> endometrial degeneration.

Secondly, it sensitises uterine contractions to prostaglandins hence why Gemeprost, a PGE1 analogue, is given with it. (Gemeprost also reduces obstetric bleeding by causing vasoconstriction)

 

Coffey's lecture

Question: Which best defines PH of systemic blood?

You and your friends decide to take a break from revision and head to Retro's for a much needed night out and to sing "Will Grigg's on fire". 

 

Upon arrival at le club, you see jager bombs are 99p, which have a high caffeine content. You know caffeine will have a positive inotropic effect on your heart and decide to stay away from it.

 

What enzyme does caffeine inhibit?
Explanation:
a) Phosphofructokinase is the rate limiting enzyme in glycolysis - it is not inhibited by caffeine.

c) Telomerase is responsible for stopping the degradation of telomeres in cells following cell division - it is often present in cancerous cells but it not inhibited by caffeine.

d) ATPase is found in many places, but is not inhibited by caffeine.

 

b) Phosphodiesterase is the correct answer. Phosphodiesterase enzymes normally break down cAMP in the cAMP-dependent intracellular signalling pathway. If phosphodiesterase is inhibited, cAMP is not broken down so the cell signalling pathway remains active. cAMP activates protein kinase A (PKA) which phosphorylates and inhibits phospholamban. This allows the opening of L-type calcium channels on the sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR) so more Ca2+ can be stored for the next heartbeat - releasing more calcium from the SR results in a positive inotropic effect, with the heart contracting more strongly.

Question: Which of the following would be the best definition for temporal summation?

OptionB: An excitatory neurone fires closely with an inhibitory neurone, causing no output.

Question: Which of the following is not a contraction factor?

In a freak accident at the labs in the heath genetically modified mice have grown to be the size of lions and have the teeth and claws to go with it. They are thirsty for blood and have been chasing you around the cochrane for 10 minutes now at full sprint. Your blood pH has dropped slightly in this time inhibiting which enzyme involved in glycolysis?
Explanation:
Phosphofructokinase-1 catalyses the conversion of Fructose-6-phosphate to fructose-1,6-bisphosphate, using a molecule of ATP in the process. When we respire anaerobically due to intense exercise etc lactic acid is produced. This lactic acid can potentially cause acidosis of the blood if we do not slow its production. Thus when pH falls inhibiting phosphofructokinase-1 we prevent/slow the progress of this occurring.

 

PFK-1 is also inhibited by ATP and up regulate by AMP.

Question:
You are well into your shift at the A&E department, You have requested a blood gas on one of the patients and the results show that their partial pressure of oxygen is less than 8KPa, but their partial pressure of carbon dioxide is normal. You suspected type 1 respiratory failure and began treatment with oxygen and go on your way.

 

A few hours later you return to see that the oxygen treatment isnt working and the patient is showing no signs of improvement. What was the cause of his respiratory failure?
Explanation:
This was in the case 5 lecture on respiratory failure. 

 

Is somebody has respiratory failure first you need to consider which type it is.

 - Type 1: Oxygenation failure: the partial pressure of oxygen will be below 8Ka but the partial pressure of carbon dioxide will be normal or slightly below. there will be an increase a-A gradient. 

 - Type 2: Ventilation failure: the partial pressure of oxygen is below 8KPa but the partial pressure of carbon dioxide is above 6KPa. there is a normal a-A gradient. 

 

knowing the type, you can then work out the treatment.

- Type 1: treat with oxygen (there will be no improvement if the failure was caused by a pulmonary shunt)

- Type 2: treat with non-invasive ventilation

Question: which one of the statements below about lung function does not occur due to increased age?
Explanation:
the effects of ageing on lung function:

 - ribcage shape can change or the bones can fuse preventing adequate expansion. 

 - respiratory muscles weaken making it harder to inspire.

 - the muscles and tissues of the airways lose their rigidity and decrease airway diameter. 

 - alveoli lose elasticity. 

 - there is a decline in the effectiveness of the lung immunological defense.

 - fibrosis occurs.

 - reduction in lung capacity.

 

Decreased mucus secretion is not something that occurs as we age.

Question: What causes increased action potential firing of the peripheral chemoreceptors involved in breathing control and regulation?

- Hypoxia is a reduction in the PaO2 which causes increased receptor firing. 

 - Hypercapnia is an increase in the PaCO2 which causes increased receptor firing.

 - Acidosis is a decrease in the blood pH which causes increased receptor firing.

Question: How does cyanide inhibit the electron transport chain?
Explanation:
Cyanide inhibits Cytochrome C Oxidase

Antimycin inhibits Co-Q- Cytochrome c  Reductase

 

Cyanide does bind to methemoglobin but this is not how it inhibits the ETC.

Nitrite can be used an as antidote to cyanide poisoning. Cyanide binds to the ferric iron on cytochrome c Oxidase. The nitrites oxidise some of the hemoglobins iron from the ferrous state to the ferric state, converting haemoglobin into methemoglobin. Cyanide binds avidly to methemoglobin, forming cyanmethemoglobin, thus releasing cyanide from  cytochrome oxidase.

Question: Where is endolymph produced?
Explanation:
Fluid waves occur in the endolymph in the various parts of the membranous labyrinth in response to fluid waves in the perilymph.

Hearing: Cochlear duct: fluid waves in the endolymph of the cochlear duct stimulate the receptor cells, which in turn translate their movement into nerve impulses that the brain perceives as sound.
Balance: Semicircular canals: angular acceleration of the endolymph in the semicircular canals stimulate the vestibular receptors of the endolymph. The semicircular canals of both inner ears act in concert to coordinate balance.

Question: Insulin increases the presence of which glucose transporter on the surface of muscle and adipose cells?
Explanation:
Muscle cells and fast cells in adipose tissue have intracellular vacuoles of the GLUT 4 glucose transporter. Insulin's main action is the movement of these to the cell surface. This will increase the uptake of glucose from the blood. 

 

GLUT 1 & GLUT 3 are found in all cells and are responsible for the basal uptake of glucose by the body. They have a low Km i.e. high affinity for glucose.

 

GLUT 2 is found in the cells of the Liver and Pancreas. It has a high Km i.e. low affinity for glucose thus it will only take up glucose when blood glucose levels are high resulting in the release of insulin *see top for action of insulin.

Question: The heart is made up of 3 layers, the epicardium is the thin external layer, what is the epicardium made up of?
OptionB: The visceral layer of the serous pericardium
OptionC: The parietal layer of the serous pericardium
Explanation:
The epicardium of the heart is the thin external layer which is made up of the visceral layer of the serous pericardium

 

Remember the order (from outer to inner):

Fibrous pericardium, then the 2 layers of the serous pericardium (first the serous parietal pericardium then the serous visceral pericardium) (remember the serous visceral pericardium is the "epicardium") (also remember the pericardical cavity containing pericardial fluid (which helps the heart to beat without friction) is in between the 2 layers of the serous pericardium), then it is the thick myocardium (made up of cardiac myocytes) and finally it is the thin endocardium inner layer which lines the inside of the heart and valves.

Question:
Look at the cell signalling pathway below taking place in a parietal cell....

 

X > activation of Gas subunit > activation of adenylyl cyclase > ATP conversion into cAMP > PKA activation > activation of H+/K+ ATPase pump

 

What is X?
Explanation:
A) B) Gastrin and CCK also activate the H+K+ATPase pump to promote HCl secretion BUT they activate Gaq not Gas. This is their pathway...

  • Gaq >  PLC  >  split PIP2 into IP3 and DAG    (IP3 goes onto release Ca2+ from ER, DAG activates PKC which in turn activates H+/K+ATPase pump
  • Only difference between the 2 is that Gastrin binds to CCKB receptors and ACh to M3 receptors

C) CORRECT (Histamine here binds to H2 receptors - drugs that block this include Ranitidine and Cimetidine)

 

D) E) These are inhibitory so they BLOCK the action of H+/K+ATPase resulting in less HCl secretion. However like Histamine, they also adopt the Adenylyl cyclase route, except they act on the Gai subunit not the Gas hence their inhibitory effect. Basically Somatostatin and Prostaglandins act in the complete opposite way that Histamine does.

 

 

 

Refer to the diagram in Jeff's lecture on this to visualise it better.

Question: Which of the following is not involved in the regulation of phosphofructose kinase (the enzyme that converts fructose-6-phosphate into fructose-1,6-bisphosphate during the glycolytic pathway)?
Explanation:
ATP binds to the allosteric site of PFK and inhibits it > decreased conversion.

AMP binds to the allosteric site of PFK in the place of ATP, stopping the ATP from inhibiting it > increased conversion.

Therefore PFK is said to be under adenylate control.

In the liver, citrate downregulates PFK and Fruc-2,6-BP upregulates PFK. 

 

A low pH also inhibits PFK  > prevents the build-up of lactic acid.

Question: what type of cell communication requires connexins?

Just to remind you about other cell junctions: adherins junctions use actin fillaments and desmosomes use intermediate fillaments.

 

gap junctions are required for juxtacrine communication, where the cells are in direct contact.

 

endocrine- hormones reach the target cell through the blood stream

paracrine- signalling molecules move to the target cell by diffusion

autocrine- the signalling molecule acts on the cell which secretes it

exorine- refers to glands which do not secrete directly into the blood e.g. salivary glands, sweat glands, exocrine pancreas

Question: 65 year old Jenny comes into the GP surgery complaining of a persistent and recent onset of heartburn after she eats or lies down. After talking to her further, you uncover that she has irritable bowel syndrome and is on warfarin. She tells you she has had diarrhoea and has been vomiting, but believes this is due to irritable bowel syndrome for which she doesn't take any medication. On palpation you find that her upper abdomen is tender. What would be the most appropriate method of action?
OptionA: Prescribe her cimetidine (a H2 receptor antagonist) and review again in a couple of weeks.
OptionB: Prescribe her with a low dose of omeprazole (a PPI) and arrange for her to have an endoscopy.
OptionC: Send her for Nissen's surgical procedure because she needs surgery to stop the acid reflux.
OptionD: As she has irritable bowel syndrome, it is likely all of her symptoms are due to this and you give her no treatment.
OptionE: Prescribe her with magnesium oxide (an antacid) and review again in a couple of weeks.
Explanation:
The correct answer is B. 

This is difficult because she has other complications, and no medication is really "ideal" for this patient. The key part here is that it would probably be wise to send her for an endoscopy. 

 

A- In this case, prescribing cimetidine wouldn't be suitable because it is a P450 inhibitor and can impair the metabolism of other drugs such as warfarin.

B- although a PPI might give her side effects of diarrhoea and therefore make her diarrhoea worse, an endoscopy would be a good idea. As she is over 55, this puts her at a higher risk of cancer or other GI complications. (being over 55 was one of the criteria for endoscopy mentioned in the lecture on dyspepsia).

C - This might end up being the treatment however it isn't the first thing you would do without investigation.

D - it is possible her diarrhoea is only due to IBS, however as she presents with symptoms from the upper GI tract such as a heartburn and abdominal tenderness, it is definitely worth investigating this.

E - Again, this would be fine however she already has diarrhoea and magnesium oxide has a side effect of osmotic diarrhoea. In this case it wouldn't be most suitable. 

 

The fact that her abdomen is tender gives a reason to investigate possible hiatus hernia or a gastric ulcer. It is important to note that you may not always feel a mass in these cases. Without further investigation you don't know whether the cause is due to an ulcer, hiatus hernia, barrett's oesophagus, achalasia (lower oesophagus doesn't relax), or just simple GORD.

Alcohol consumption is a risk factor for conditions that affect the stomach (particularly the stomach lining) such as gastritis. What is the mechanism by which alcohol affects the normal physiology of the stomach?
OptionA: Creates ROS that bind to and activate H+/K+ ATPase (proton pump), thus increasing H+ release. (More stomach acid)
OptionB: Interferes with ACh release, hence ACh cannot bind to M3 receptors. This leads to decreased H+ release making the stomach less protected from pathogens.
OptionC: Reverses the action of H+/K+ ATPase (proton pump) hence the parietal cells become excessively acidic and die.
OptionD: Stimulates surface mucous producing cells on the epithelium lining and leads to the production of an insoluble mucous which leaves the stomach lining more vulnerable to stomach acid.
OptionE: Transiently binds to H2 receptors and stimulates excess gastric acid secretion.
Explanation:
In the gastric pits of the stomach on the epithelium layer there are mucous neck cells which secrete mucous in response to vagal stimulation. There are also surface secreting mucous cells; they differ from the mucous neck cells and instead of vagal stimulation, they are stimulated by alcohol consumption. Another difference is that when the surface secreting mucosal cells are stimulated they secrete an insoluble mucous which is not able to protect the stomach lining from the stomach acid and this can lead to gastric erosion. 

 

Furthermore, alcohol has been shown to bring about abnormalities of the pressure of lower oesophageal sphincter and oesophageal motility, thus predisposing the patient to GORD.

http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2880354/

This is definitely a bit more challenging as it involves some derivation!

Question: When does the oocyte complete meiosis II?
OptionD: During the transition form a secondary follicle to a Graafian follicle
OptionE: During the transition from a primary follicle to a graafian follicle
Explanation:
Before birth oogonium undergo mitosis, producing primary oocytes surrounded by a single layer of pre-granulosa cells.  The primary oocyte inside starts to divide by meiosis but this arrests in prophase I.

 

At puberty, development of primordial cells is stimulated, into primary follicles, then secondary follies and by the time a Graafian follicle is developed, the oocyte has completed its first meiotic division and is now a secondary oocyte.  The secondary oocyte starts meiosis II but this arrests in metaphase II. 

 

After ovulation, (secondary oocyte released surrounded by some granulosa cells) if sperm penetrates the secondary oocyte, Meiosis II will complete producing an ovum i.e. entry of sperm triggers the transition form metaphase II to anaphase II. This happens before the fusion of DNA.

A patient comes into your GP surgery presenting with penile discharge and dysuria. After you have run tests, you diagnose him with gonorrhoea. To treat him, the patient is given antibiotics (doxycycline and ceftriaxone). 3 weeks later he returns to see you, saying that his symptoms have come back, despite him not having sex since he was diagnosed with gonorrhoea. You treat him again, but he then returns 2 weeks after this, with the same symptoms. What is the most likely reason that he is getting recurring symptoms of gonorrhoea?
OptionA: He is resistant to the antibiotics he is being given.
OptionB: He has actually had sex since and got gonorrhoea again.
OptionD: He has a deficiency in C5b/C6-C9 complement proteins.
OptionE: He has a deficiency in vitamin B2
Explanation:
D is the correct answer, because a deficiency in one of the complement proteins that form the MAC (i.e. C5b or C6-C9) results in no MAC formation. This can specifically cause recurrent Neisseria infections. Gonorrhoea is caused by the bacterium Neisseria gonorrhoeae and so his recurrent infections are down to his deficiency in one of these complement proteins. Meningitis is also a type of Neisseria infection.

 

A: resistance to these antibiotics (ceftriaxone and doxycycline) is unlikely (although presumably not impossible) so it is not the single best answer for this question. Resistance rates are, however, high when using antibiotics such as penicillin and tetracycline. Ceftriaxone is apparently one of the few effective antibiotics left for gonorrhoea. 

 

B: potentially true but again, probably unlikely that he would have contracted gonorrhoea twice more in this time. 

 

C: Neutrophilia = high levels of neutrophils in the blood. Not really relevant here - neutropenia may be more relevant though. 

 

E: Not relevant -B2 deficiency causes stomatitis (although it can cause scrotal skin rashes, but this isn't one of the symptoms the patient presents with).
Tags: STIs, Case 2, PCS unit 2, Immunology, vitamins and minerals

OptionB: They inhibit PGHS-2 derived PGE2 which normally sensitises A-beta and A-delta fibres to serotonin, bradykinin and substance P

Question: Which is not a cause of the main NSAID ADRs?
OptionA: The acidic molecules directly irritate the gastric mucosal, causing an increased risk of gastric ulceration
OptionB: NSAIDs block the prostaglandin-mediated effect of vasodilation of the afferent arteriole, therefore causing vasoconstriction of the afferent arteriole and decreased renal perfusion pressure
OptionC: Inhibition of COX-1 and COX-2 reduces protective prostaglandins, causing an increased risk of gastric ulceration
OptionD: NSAIDs block the prostaglandin-mediated effect of vasoconstriction of the afferent arteriole, therefore causing vasodilation of the afferent arteriole and decreased renal perfusion pressure.
Explanation:
A: this is an cause of gastric ulceration which is a common NSAID ADR

B: this is a cause of compromised renal function which is an NSAID ADR

C: this is a cause of gastric ulceration which is a common NSAID ADR

D: this is the answer. Prostaglandins normally cause vasodilation of the afferent arteriole (not vasoconstriction). Therefore inhibition of this would cause vasoconstriction of the afferent arteriole (not vasodilation), causing decreased renal perfusion pressure.  

 

More info on why constriction causes decreased renal perfusion pressure (copied from wiki):

 

Normally the afferent arteriole is of larger diameter than the efferent. This means there is high resistance as the blood is forced from a wider vessel to a narrower one and this promotes filtration. If the arterial blood pressure remains constant then contracting either vessel reduces blood flow as it increases resistance. However contracting either has opposite effects on the filtration pressure. If you contract the afferent arteriole there will be less of a pressure difference between the afferent and efferent arteriole so there will be reduced filtration pressure. However if you constrict the efferent arteriole you are increasing the pressure difference between the two and filtration pressure increase.

Overall the constriction of the afferent arteriole decreases both blood flow and filtration pressure where as constricting the efferent arteriole decreases blood flow but increases filtration pressure. (Both of these statements are assuming a constant blood pressure). The fact that both can be altered allows independent regulation of both GFR and blood flow.

E - this is technically correct but is too unspecific/ambiguous.

Question:
John is a first year medical student. He has taken up weightlifting, in a drastic attempt to recover from the humiliation of losing an arm wrestle to his 16 year-old brother. He trains 4 times a week and is eating up to 4000 kcal a day to ensure he continues to make what he describes as 'gains'.

 

What sort of cellular changes are occurring in John's skeletal muscle?
Explanation:
The answer is of course hypertrophy.

 

Hypertrophy is an increase in cell size but not cell number. Skeletal muscle growth in response to exercise is a physiological example, and ventricular hypertrophy is a pathological example.

 

Hyperplasia is an increase in cell number, which can, for example, occur in the uterus during pregnancy.

 

Metaplasia is a change in cell type, for example Barret's oesophagus.

 

Atrophy is a decrease in cell size, which occurs with lower motor neuron lesions.

 

Dysplasia is an abnormal hyperplasia, for example tumour growth.

 

(Update: John's brother also took up weightlifting and the embarrassment continues...)

Question: At 90dB the safe exposure time is 4 hours. At what intensity will the safe exposure time be 22mins 30 secs?
Explanation:
A rise of 3 dB represents a doubling in sound energy so safe exposure time halves with each 3 dB increase. 

 

The question isn't easy if maths isn't your forte but basically the safe exposure time has halved 3 and half times: 4 > 2 > 1 > 30 > (22.30) 

 

Therefore the sound intensity must have increased 3.5 x 3 = 10.5 dB 

 

So the sound intensity must be 90 + 10.5 = 100.5 dB

Question: How does simethicone work?
OptionA: Reduces bloating, discomfort and pain caused by excessive gas.
OptionB: Increases surface tension of gas bubbles, causing the to combine into larger bubbles in the stomach which pass more easily.
OptionC: Reduces the formation of gas in the digestive tract.

OptionE: Increases surface tension of gas bubbles, causing them to break away into smaller bubbles in the stomach which can pass more easily.
Explanation:
Simethicone is an anti-foaming agent, often used alongside antacids. 

 

A - this is why anti-foaming agents are used, but doesn't really describe in enough detail how they work.

B - an increase in surface tension would not cause bubbles to combine to form larger bubbles - a decrease in surface tension would do this.

C - this is incorrect. Anti-foaming agents do not reduce or prevent the formation of gas in the digestive tract but instead, they increase the rate at which it exits the body.

D - this is the correct answer.

E - it is larger bubbles that are passed more easily not smaller bubbles (and also, antifoaming agents cause a decrease in surface tension, not an increase). I'm not sure why smaller bubbles are more difficult to pass - if anybody has any ideas, please comment :)

Question: How do proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) work?
OptionB: Upregulate the H+/K+ ATPase pump on parietal cells, causing more H+ to be removed from the gastric lumen and reuptaken into parietal cells
OptionC: Irreversibly block the H+/K+ ATPase pump on parietal cells, preventing secretion of H+ ions into the gastric lumen
OptionD: Irreversibly blocks the H+/Na+ ATPase pump on parietal cells, preventing secretion of H+ into the gastric lumen

Explanation:
A - this describes the action of antacids, which combine with HCl to form a salt and water.

B - as the name suggest, proton pump inhibitors inhibit the H+/K+ pump they don't upregulate it.

C - this is the correct answer. The proton pump is the terminal stage in gastric acid secretion, being directly responsible for secreting H+ ions into the gastric lumen.

D - PPIs block the H+/K+ ATPase pump not the H+/Na+ ATPase pump

E - this describes alginates (which are used with antacids)

Question: What is the Z line?

Explanation:

D - this is the correct answer. The stratified squamous epithelia of the oesophagus is better suited to the abrasion of food than simple columnar.

 

A way to remember these metaplasias is just that stratified squamous epithelia is suited to areas of high abrasion like the vagina or oesophagus and then changes to simple columnar where areas of lower abrasion are reached such as the cervix and the stomach.

Question: Which antibody is found in urine, and helps to protect against UTI's?
Which kind of UTI causing bacteria have urease - a chemical which can split urea, altering the pH of urine and making stones more likely?

What are bacterial cell walls made of?

 

Hint - they are a target for antibiotics...
Explanation:
Bacteria are usually classified as Gram + or Gram-, which is based on a particular staining method. Gram + are bacteria that have one plasma membrane, surrounded by a thick cell wall, which is made up of so called peptidoglycan, which acts as a sort of exo-skeleton. Gram – bacteria have two cell membranes: the inner membrane and the outer membrane. Between the inner and outer membrane is the cell wall, similar to that of Gram + bacteria, just usually thinner. The synthesis of the cell wall is the major target of antibiotics. The main group of antibiotics in this class are the beta lactam antibiotics, they all have a similar structure the beta lactam ring. These antibiotics, to which the penicillins and cephalosporins belong, act by inhibiting a protein called penicillin binding protein (PBP), which causes cross linking of the peptidoglycan in the cell wall. Inhibiting this action, weakens the cell wall.

There are some bacteria, e.g. mycoplasma and ureaplasma that don’t have a cell wall and thus cannot be targeted by cell wall synthesis inhibitors.

Question: Why does Crigler-Najjar syndrome cause jaundice?

Question:
We have an enzyme conforming to the Michealis-Menten Equation. 

The value of Km=9. What substrate concentration will give a velocity which is 1/4 of Vmax.
Explanation:
Right let's use Michealis-Menten equation to work this all out. 

Here V = Vmax[S]/ Km+ [S]

 

We know Km and we can work out Vmax by 2x9 = 18.

 

We then can also work out V at 1/4 Vmax- 18/4 = 4.5. 

 

Then put this back into the equation. 

 

We get 4.5 = 18 x [S]/ 9 + [S] 

 

Rearrange so 9+[S] = 18[S] / 4.5 [S]

 

9+[S] = 4 [S] 

 

- [S] from both sides 

 

9= 3[S] 

 

[S]= 3.

Question:
You are observing consultations with your GP tutor when a mother arrives with her 19 year-old daughter. Upon questioning, the GP ascertains that the girl has amenorrhoea and chronic hyperphagia.

 

Her height is 162cm.

Her weight is 90kg.

Her MOCA score is 29.

 

What is the likely diagnosis?
Explanation:
The critical weight hypothesis means that females must reach a high enough weight before starting puberty to prevent them from becoming pregnant when they don't have sufficient energy stored (as fat).

Adipopcytes secrete leptin which has a positive effect on the reproductive axis (GnRH and all that), hence causing the onset of puberty.

Someone with leptin deficiency would have amenorrhoea as their reproductive axis would not get stimulated by leptin.

 

Additionally, leptin is released by adipocytes after meals to make us feel full. This is why the patient has chronic hyperphagia. As a result her BMI is 34.2, so she is very obese.

Question: What does the myocardium look like 6 hours after a myocardial infarction?
OptionC: Other non-infarcted areas of the myocardium undergo hypertrophy to compensate
Explanation:
A - refers to what the myocardium would look like in the weeks following the MI (probably after about 7 weeks)

B - refers to the remodelling of the myocardium which would occur in the weeks-months following the MI

C - also refers to the remodelling of the myocardium, occurring weeks-months following an MI; the hypertrophy is compensatory for the death of the infarcted tissue

D - this is the correct answer; occurs because of the lack of red blood reaching the area

E - refers to what the myocardium would look like after 24 hours; this is due to haemorrhage of the area

 

The myocardium goes from being pale soon after infarction, to red, to yellowing in the middle which spreads to the borders and gradually becomes grey/white as the scarring is completed.

Question: What is the S1 heart sound caused by?

OptionC: Stiffening of the ventricular walls, producing turbulent flow as the atria contract to force blood into the ventricle
OptionD: Oscillations of blood back and forth between the ventricle walls initiated by blood rushing in from the atria
Explanation:
A: this describes the S2 heart sound - "dub" of  the "lub-dub" sound

B: this is the correct answer and describes the S1 heart sound - the "lub" of the "lub-dub" sound

C: this describes the S4 heart sound, which is pathological, usually caused by failing/hypertrophic left ventricle - the "la" in "la-lub-dub"

D: this describes the S3 heart sound, which is not usually heard but can be normal in youth, pregnancy and trained athletes. It may, in some patients however, be a sign of a cardiac problem. It occurs immediately after S2, during diastole

Question:
A patient presents with jaundice, fever and malaise. They have a history of drug abuse when you look at past medical history. 

You decide to investigate their Hepatitis B status as you suspect this could be an episode of acute HBV infection. 

The results come back as:

HBsAg  positive 

anti-HBc   positive
IgM anti-HBc   positive
anti-HBs   negative

 

What is your diagnosis?
Explanation:
The answer is C based on both the medical history and presenting complaint but also the serology presented.

 

Let's go through each serological result. 

 

HBsAg- HBV surface antigen. Only present if there is an infection within the body. Therefore we can establish that this person has been infected with HBV. 

 

anti-Hbc - antigen to HBV core protein. You make this protein with an acute infection and also it persists for life if you recover from the virus. Here we can see that this is present, but would also be in a chronic infection. 

 

IgM anti-Hbc - immunoglobulin. Presence indicates a recent infection, this gives us the clue that it is an acute infection. 

 

anti-HbS- usually only present in a resolved infection, given that this not present here we can say that it has not been resolved.

 

Overall; acute infection.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

SOURCE: https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HBV/PDFs/SerologicChartv8.pdf really good.

Question:
Barbara goes to the doctors and wants a general STI screening. She also decides to get BBV checked.

 

Her serology results come back: 

 

HBsAg positive
anti-HBc positive
IgM anti-HBc negative
anti-HBs negative

 

What is your diagnosis based on serology?
Explanation:
The answer is C based on both the medical history and presenting complaint but also the serology presented.

Let's go through each serological result.

HBsAg- HBV surface antigen. Only present if there is an infection within the body. Therefore we can establish that this person has been infected with HBV.

 

anti-Hbc - antigen to HBV core protein. You make this protein with an acute infection and also it persists for life if you recover from the virus. Here we can see that this is present, but would also be in an acute infection.

 

IgM anti-Hbc - immunoglobulin. Presence indicates a recent infection, this gives us the clue that it is an acute infection. Since this is not present, suggests that Babs was infected over 6 months ago, therefore we can classify this as chronic. 

 

anti-HbS- usually only present in a resolved infection, given that this not present here we can say that it has not been resolved.

 

Overall; chronic infection.

anti-Hbc - antigen to HBV core protein. You make this protein with an acute infection and also it persists for life if you recover from the virus. Here we can see that this is present, but would also be in an acute infection.

Whilst there is excess Growth Hormone secreted in this condition, it is the excessive release of IGF-1 (insulin-like growth factor)- stimulated to be released  from this liver by Growth hormone -  which physically causes the high linear growth due to the excessive action of IGF-1  when the epiphyseal growth plates are open. This stimulates the over growth of bones causing the excessive height and also soft tissue iproportions are also affected. 

 

Acromegaly is different from this. This occur when there is excessive growth hormone later in life. This causes the course facial features, enlarged hands and feet and the cardiomegaly.

Question: What is the condition shown below?
Explanation:
It is indeed vesico-ureteric reflux. There are 2 types of this condition:

 

• Primary VUR is present at birth. It is caused by a defect in the development of the ureter valve (prevents backflow of blood). This is the most common type of VUR and is usually detected shortly after birth.

 

• Secondary VUR occurs when an obstruction in the bladder or urethra causes urine to flow backward into the kidneys. Secondary VUR can occur at any age and can be caused by surgery, injury, a pattern of emptying the bladder that's not normal, or a past infection that puts pressure on the bladder. It is more common in children who have other birth defects, (such as spina bifida).

Question: Haram Boyz have kicked off 2k16 and shutdown Cardiff. They are called in for a confidential meeting regarding professionalism.... and are nervous they might be failed for the year. Question: What is UDP-glucuronosyl transferase (UGT)?
OptionA: A phase I metabolite enzyme that oxidatively modifies a drug to create a reactive group
OptionB: A phase II metabolite enzyme that oxidatively modifies a drug to create a reactive group
OptionC: A phase I metabolite enzyme that conjugates glucuronide to the drug to make it water soluble
OptionD: A phase II metabolite enzyme that conjugates glucuronide to the drug to make it water soluble
Explanation:
The main group of phase I metabolite enzymes is CYP (cytochrome p450) which is for oxidative modification of the drug. It has a catalytic haem group and is an "on-demand" enzyme so is only induced when the metabolite is detected.

 

The main type of phase II metabolite is UGT which conjugates a water-soluble glucuronide to the drug and also de-activates its pharmacological activity. It is the enzyme used to conjugate bilirubin so people with Gilbert's or Crigler-najjar syndromes with mutated/deleted UGT1A1 have a build of of unconjugated bilirubin and hence jaundice

Question:
Familial Hypercholesterolaemia is a condition that can cause patients to suffer from coronary heart disease 20 years earlier than those without it. It is due to either a a mutation in the LDL receptor or a mutation in the receptor.

 

Which of these is a receptor most associated with LDL?
Explanation:
ApoA1 is a receptor for HDL - the 'hoover' of LDL and cholesterol, performing the reverse cholesterol pathway


ApoB48 is a chylomicron receptor. Chylomicrons are TAG transporters, transporting them from the gut to the liver in the exogenous pathway. Please note that when chylomicrons become chylomicron remnants in the exogenous pathway, they then use ApoE as a receptor in the liver.

 

ApoB100 is correct! LDL is formed from IDL in the endogenous pathway by hepatic lipase, and is taken up in adipose tissue and the liver by these receptors.

 

ApoCII is actually a cofactor lipoprotein lipase for VLDL. When VLDL finishes this process and has lost its fats it becomes IDL

 

ApoE is used for both chylomicron remnants and IDL, which are both absorbed by the liver.

 

Source - Lipids and CV Disease lecture - case 4, along with the Geeky medics site for info that Dr McDowell recommended
